00:00:05.414 --> 00:00:06.580
JAKE TAPPER: Thanks so much.

00:00:06.580 --> 00:00:07.621
It's so great to be here.

00:00:07.621 --> 00:00:09.940
I really appreciate it.

00:00:09.940 --> 00:00:11.440
Just first of all,
I should tell you

00:00:11.440 --> 00:00:13.360
I wrote the book on Google Docs.

00:00:13.360 --> 00:00:15.230
I don't know if that
means anything--

00:00:15.230 --> 00:00:16.660
if that means anything to you.

00:00:16.660 --> 00:00:20.080
But the idea that I could
bring my computer or not bring

00:00:20.080 --> 00:00:23.770
my computer, and just wherever
I was-- at work or on the road--

00:00:23.770 --> 00:00:25.576
I could write and pick
up where I left off,

00:00:25.576 --> 00:00:26.950
not have to worry
about it saving

00:00:26.950 --> 00:00:28.810
since it saves automatically--

00:00:28.810 --> 00:00:30.430
it's a great product
and it really

00:00:30.430 --> 00:00:33.160
helped me write the book.

00:00:33.160 --> 00:00:35.800
So I'll just talk a
little bit about the book.

00:00:35.800 --> 00:00:38.440
And then, I'll take
your questions.

00:00:38.440 --> 00:00:41.590
I guess, when I think
of "The Hellfire Club,"

00:00:41.590 --> 00:00:43.230
I think of it on
three basic levels.

00:00:43.230 --> 00:00:44.950
One of them is this--

00:00:44.950 --> 00:00:48.710
I tried to write a thriller,
what I thought would be fun.

00:00:48.710 --> 00:00:50.760
It takes place in 1954.

00:00:50.760 --> 00:00:53.410
A World War II hero
turned academic

00:00:53.410 --> 00:00:55.390
named Charlie Marder
and his wife, Margaret,

00:00:55.390 --> 00:00:57.820
who is a zoologist,
moved to Washington DC.

00:00:57.820 --> 00:01:00.670
He gets appointed to
a congressional seat.

00:01:00.670 --> 00:01:06.190
And immediately, they become
ensnared in a grand conspiracy

00:01:06.190 --> 00:01:08.410
with secret societies
and all sorts of factions

00:01:08.410 --> 00:01:10.472
competing against each other.

00:01:10.472 --> 00:01:12.430
One of the things that
I thought would be fun--

00:01:12.430 --> 00:01:13.930
and I hope is fun for readers--

00:01:13.930 --> 00:01:18.880
is I have actual
people from that time--

00:01:18.880 --> 00:01:23.080
like Joe McCarthy, and Roy Cohn,
and John and Robert Kennedy,

00:01:23.080 --> 00:01:25.030
and Eisenhower, and
others-- interacting

00:01:25.030 --> 00:01:29.830
with my fictitious characters,
which I thought would be fun.

00:01:29.830 --> 00:01:32.440
People ask me all the
time, why the 1950s?

00:01:32.440 --> 00:01:37.450
And I think of the 1950s as
a time that, on its veneer--

00:01:37.450 --> 00:01:39.850
especially, if
you're a white male--

00:01:39.850 --> 00:01:42.790
it is an idyllic period.

00:01:42.790 --> 00:01:45.490
In our popular culture,
we think of "Happy Days"

00:01:45.490 --> 00:01:46.510
or "American Graffiti."

00:01:46.510 --> 00:01:49.330
We think of the '50s
as a pleasant time.

00:01:49.330 --> 00:01:51.910
But actually, it was
a time of real menace.

00:01:51.910 --> 00:01:54.520
You had actual communists
infiltrating the government.

00:01:54.520 --> 00:01:56.260
You had McCarthyism
and the Red Scare.

00:01:56.260 --> 00:01:59.200
You had the atomic race.

00:01:59.200 --> 00:02:03.250
In March, 1954, Puerto
Rican separatists burst

00:02:03.250 --> 00:02:04.720
into the capitol
and shoot it up,

00:02:04.720 --> 00:02:06.640
and shoot five
members of the House.

00:02:06.640 --> 00:02:08.530
There are the bizarre
comic book hearings,

00:02:08.530 --> 00:02:11.350
where the US Senate is
blaming juvenile delinquency

00:02:11.350 --> 00:02:13.120
on comic books.

00:02:13.120 --> 00:02:15.050
Any of you who
collect comic books--

00:02:15.050 --> 00:02:18.980
and I'm guessing at Google,
it's probably a few--

00:02:18.980 --> 00:02:20.572
the little Comics
Code Authority--

00:02:20.572 --> 00:02:22.780
the little tag on the front
page of the comic books--

00:02:22.780 --> 00:02:25.000
is a remnant of
that ridiculous era.

00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:26.720
So I thought it would be fun.

00:02:26.720 --> 00:02:29.920
I thought it would be just an
exciting time to write about.

00:02:29.920 --> 00:02:32.680
That's one level I
think about the book.

00:02:32.680 --> 00:02:36.940
Another level I think about
the book is Charlie Marder--

00:02:36.940 --> 00:02:40.420
one of the two main characters--
comes to Washington to do good.

00:02:40.420 --> 00:02:42.190
And one of the first
things he tries to do

00:02:42.190 --> 00:02:46.510
is to stop a company-- a
rubber and tire company that

00:02:46.510 --> 00:02:49.240
made bad gas masks
during World War II--

00:02:49.240 --> 00:02:51.280
stop them from getting
any federal money.

00:02:51.280 --> 00:02:53.230
And he finds out that
in order to do good,

00:02:53.230 --> 00:02:55.480
he needs to make compromises.

00:02:55.480 --> 00:02:59.800
And this is something that I've
just noticed in Washington DC,

00:02:59.800 --> 00:03:02.410
having lived there
now, basically,

00:03:02.410 --> 00:03:04.850
since the end of 1992--

00:03:04.850 --> 00:03:06.374
which is really good people--

00:03:06.374 --> 00:03:08.290
Democrats, and Republicans,
and Independents--

00:03:08.290 --> 00:03:10.300
come to town to do good things.

00:03:10.300 --> 00:03:11.470
They want to do good.

00:03:11.470 --> 00:03:17.109
And a lot of them get trapped
in a cycle of compromise,

00:03:17.109 --> 00:03:19.400
where they dip one foot into
the swamp and another foot

00:03:19.400 --> 00:03:20.130
into the swamp.

00:03:20.130 --> 00:03:22.380
And the next thing they know,
they're up to their neck

00:03:22.380 --> 00:03:24.254
in swamp and they don't
know how to get out.

00:03:24.254 --> 00:03:25.670
So that was another
thing I wanted

00:03:25.670 --> 00:03:28.460
to try to capture
in the book, is just

00:03:28.460 --> 00:03:30.800
the idea of why it happens--

00:03:30.800 --> 00:03:33.470
that so many good people
that you believe in,

00:03:33.470 --> 00:03:35.240
you look up and 10
years later, and you're

00:03:35.240 --> 00:03:38.359
like, whatever happened to her
or whatever happened to him?

00:03:38.359 --> 00:03:40.400
I used to think that that
person was pretty cool,

00:03:40.400 --> 00:03:41.730
and now they're not.

00:03:41.730 --> 00:03:43.521
Which is not to say
that there aren't still

00:03:43.521 --> 00:03:45.290
a lot of really good
people in Congress.

00:03:45.290 --> 00:03:46.220
There are.

00:03:46.220 --> 00:03:48.036
The heroes of the
book are politicians

00:03:48.036 --> 00:03:49.910
and the villains of the
book are politicians,

00:03:49.910 --> 00:03:52.070
so they're both covered.

00:03:52.070 --> 00:03:55.520
And then, the last
thing is, in addition

00:03:55.520 --> 00:03:59.540
to the swamp, the thing
that I think is resonant

00:03:59.540 --> 00:04:01.490
for a lot of readers is--

00:04:01.490 --> 00:04:02.570
and this was--

00:04:02.570 --> 00:04:06.080
I started writing
this book years ago.

00:04:06.080 --> 00:04:08.600
And if you set a book
in 1954, and you're

00:04:08.600 --> 00:04:09.789
going to have people--

00:04:09.789 --> 00:04:12.080
characters-- interacting with
real people from the era,

00:04:12.080 --> 00:04:13.654
obviously Roy Cohn
and Joe McCarthy

00:04:13.654 --> 00:04:16.070
are going to be obvious people
you're going to seize upon.

00:04:16.070 --> 00:04:21.311
I did not know at the time
that Roy Cohn's protégé,

00:04:21.311 --> 00:04:23.810
Donald Trump, was going to be
president of the United States

00:04:23.810 --> 00:04:25.060
by the time the book came out.

00:04:25.060 --> 00:04:28.970
But it turns out there is this
connective tissue that Senator

00:04:28.970 --> 00:04:31.790
McCarthy's protégé was Roy
Cohn, and Roy Cohn's protégé was

00:04:31.790 --> 00:04:32.630
Donald Trump.

00:04:32.630 --> 00:04:34.040
That's nothing I invented.

00:04:34.040 --> 00:04:36.750
It just is a reality.

00:04:36.750 --> 00:04:44.630
And so diving into the 1950s
and reading about the time

00:04:44.630 --> 00:04:47.540
of McCarthyism-- and
I don't want to--

00:04:47.540 --> 00:04:50.510
Donald Trump and Joe McCarthy
are not the same person,

00:04:50.510 --> 00:04:54.050
and Trumpism and McCarthyism
are not the same thing.

00:04:54.050 --> 00:05:00.620
But the occurrence of a major
political figure using lying,

00:05:00.620 --> 00:05:05.180
and smearing, and
indecency as his method

00:05:05.180 --> 00:05:11.150
of art in his political
warfare has happened before.

00:05:11.150 --> 00:05:16.910
And reading about people
and how political figures

00:05:16.910 --> 00:05:22.140
acted or didn't act at the
time was very instructive.

00:05:22.140 --> 00:05:23.930
So some of the book--

00:05:23.930 --> 00:05:25.400
not a lot of it--

00:05:25.400 --> 00:05:27.080
I might have played
up a little bit,

00:05:27.080 --> 00:05:29.420
or I did play up a little
bit, because of the era

00:05:29.420 --> 00:05:31.235
that we're in.

00:05:31.235 --> 00:05:33.110
But the rhyming-- you
know, they say, history

00:05:33.110 --> 00:05:35.600
doesn't repeat
itself, but it rhymes.

00:05:35.600 --> 00:05:39.450
And the rhyming
was already there,

00:05:39.450 --> 00:05:41.090
and so there is some of that.

00:05:41.090 --> 00:05:44.492
I thought I'd read one
really quick scene to you.

00:05:44.492 --> 00:05:45.950
I want to apologize
ahead of time--

00:05:45.950 --> 00:05:47.750
especially to a Boston crowd--

00:05:47.750 --> 00:05:53.120
because I am going to do
Robert Kennedy's voice.

00:05:53.120 --> 00:05:57.750
And I want you to know that I
don't think I do it very well,

00:05:57.750 --> 00:05:58.760
but I can't not do it.

00:06:01.550 --> 00:06:07.520
One of the thrills about writing
this book was the research.

00:06:07.520 --> 00:06:10.100
I know I'm in a room full of
people who like to do research.

00:06:10.100 --> 00:06:17.570
And last year, I did an event
for the 100th anniversary

00:06:17.570 --> 00:06:19.520
of the birth of John F. Kennedy.

00:06:19.520 --> 00:06:22.800
And I met Kathleen
Kennedy Townsend,

00:06:22.800 --> 00:06:25.850
who is Robert
Kennedy's oldest child.

00:06:25.850 --> 00:06:29.150
And I was doing-- you know, I
was in the thick of research.

00:06:29.150 --> 00:06:31.670
And actually, I had
read in several books

00:06:31.670 --> 00:06:35.660
that her godfather was Joe
McCarthy, because the Kennedys

00:06:35.660 --> 00:06:38.270
and Joe McCarthy
were very close.

00:06:38.270 --> 00:06:39.596
So I fact checked it with her.

00:06:39.596 --> 00:06:40.970
And she said, no,
it wasn't true,

00:06:40.970 --> 00:06:43.340
but they were very close--
the families were very close.

00:06:43.340 --> 00:06:49.320
And I asked her why, because Joe
McCarthy was a horrible person.

00:06:49.320 --> 00:06:52.930
And she said it was very tribal
because they were all Irish,

00:06:52.930 --> 00:06:54.770
and the '40s and
the '50s were still

00:06:54.770 --> 00:06:58.160
a period where the Irish
were looked down upon.

00:06:58.160 --> 00:07:02.210
And no matter how much
the Kennedys achieved,

00:07:02.210 --> 00:07:05.450
the Boston Brahmins still
looked down their noses

00:07:05.450 --> 00:07:06.560
at the Kennedys.

00:07:06.560 --> 00:07:08.684
And so they bonded that way.

00:07:08.684 --> 00:07:10.100
Then another time,
I was reading--

00:07:10.100 --> 00:07:11.766
when I was doing
research for the book--

00:07:11.766 --> 00:07:15.080
I was reading a Ted Sorensen
biography of John F. Kennedy.

00:07:15.080 --> 00:07:19.700
And Sorensen kept referring
to Robert Kennedy as Bob--

00:07:19.700 --> 00:07:22.850
Bob Kennedy-- which I had
never heard before in my life,

00:07:22.850 --> 00:07:25.610
and I'm something of
a student of history.

00:07:25.610 --> 00:07:27.980
And so I emailed Kathleen
Kennedy Townsend,

00:07:27.980 --> 00:07:30.720
did people call your dad Bob,
because I'm reading this book?

00:07:30.720 --> 00:07:34.910
And she said, yeah, that's
what they called him.

00:07:34.910 --> 00:07:37.372
So I have a character in the
book correcting somebody.

00:07:37.372 --> 00:07:38.330
Nobody calls him Bobby.

00:07:38.330 --> 00:07:41.000
Anybody who knows
him calls him Bob.

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:43.760
Now, I told this anecdote
at a publishing event

00:07:43.760 --> 00:07:48.080
about a year ago, forgetting
that one of Robert Kennedy's

00:07:48.080 --> 00:07:50.060
other kids was in the audience.

00:07:50.060 --> 00:07:51.560
He had, like, 100.

00:07:51.560 --> 00:07:57.080
And this one was Kerry
Kennedy Cuomo, I think.

00:07:59.665 --> 00:08:01.790
I was doing a presentation
for "The Hellfire Club."

00:08:01.790 --> 00:08:04.880
She was doing a
presentation for a book that

00:08:04.880 --> 00:08:07.130
was commemorating the 50th
anniversary of her father's

00:08:07.130 --> 00:08:08.240
assassination.

00:08:08.240 --> 00:08:10.490
And she-- after I told that
story about Bob and Robert

00:08:10.490 --> 00:08:11.310
and Bobby--

00:08:11.310 --> 00:08:12.980
she went on stage
and corrected me.

00:08:12.980 --> 00:08:14.620
She said, it wasn't
necessarily true.

00:08:14.620 --> 00:08:15.430
People called him Bob.

00:08:15.430 --> 00:08:16.270
Some people called him Bobby.

00:08:16.270 --> 00:08:17.650
Some people called him senator.

00:08:17.650 --> 00:08:19.441
And I went up to her
afterwards and I said,

00:08:19.441 --> 00:08:23.110
you know, your oldest
sister is the one

00:08:23.110 --> 00:08:24.490
who told me the Bob thing.

00:08:24.490 --> 00:08:27.450
And I'm an oldest
child in my family.

00:08:27.450 --> 00:08:31.720
And I know who has the
most credible information

00:08:31.720 --> 00:08:34.450
in any family, and that
is the oldest child.

00:08:34.450 --> 00:08:37.480
We are the keepers of history.

00:08:37.480 --> 00:08:40.460
So anyway, I took
it as a good sign

00:08:40.460 --> 00:08:43.870
that Kathleen Kennedy Townsend's
daughter came to one of my book

00:08:43.870 --> 00:08:45.220
events in Washington DC.

00:08:45.220 --> 00:08:47.230
I took it as
official recognition

00:08:47.230 --> 00:08:48.460
that I had it right.

00:08:48.460 --> 00:08:51.280
The oldest child is correct.

00:08:51.280 --> 00:08:53.200
So this is just a quick
scene just to give you

00:08:53.200 --> 00:08:59.130
a taste of the
book, where Charlie

00:08:59.130 --> 00:09:04.120
is at a fancy party at the
Mayflower Hotel in Washington

00:09:04.120 --> 00:09:08.140
being thrown by Conrad Hilton
after Congress passed a bill

00:09:08.140 --> 00:09:10.690
to let cheap Mexican
labor come over the border

00:09:10.690 --> 00:09:13.600
more easily, which they actually
did that actual day-- or that

00:09:13.600 --> 00:09:15.610
actual week.

00:09:15.610 --> 00:09:18.100
And Charlie goes,
and he and Roy Cohn

00:09:18.100 --> 00:09:20.080
start getting into a fight--

00:09:20.080 --> 00:09:20.870
an argument.

00:09:20.870 --> 00:09:22.900
Roy Cohn is such a fun character
to write because you could just

00:09:22.900 --> 00:09:24.760
make him be really
smart and just the worst

00:09:24.760 --> 00:09:29.240
person in the world, except
for possibly Joe McCarthy.

00:09:29.240 --> 00:09:31.360
So anyway, at this
point, Robert Kennedy--

00:09:31.360 --> 00:09:35.530
Bob Kennedy-- walks in and tries
to settle the two because they

00:09:35.530 --> 00:09:38.020
seem to be squaring off.

00:09:38.020 --> 00:09:40.690
And again, I apologize
for my Kennedy accent.

00:09:40.690 --> 00:09:43.150
""Evening Roy,' Bob Kennedy
said, approaching them.

00:09:43.150 --> 00:09:46.537
Recognizing Charlie,
he said, 'Congressman.'

00:09:46.537 --> 00:09:49.120
'Charlie Marder,' Charlie said,
not sure if Kennedy remembered

00:09:49.120 --> 00:09:50.230
his name.

00:09:50.230 --> 00:09:51.790
In Washington,
Charlie had noticed

00:09:51.790 --> 00:09:55.150
people tended to avoid names
in case they got them wrong.

00:09:55.150 --> 00:09:57.190
They tended to say,
nice to see you,

00:09:57.190 --> 00:10:01.480
instead of nice to meet you, in
case they had met you before.

00:10:01.480 --> 00:10:04.150
New social rules
for an egoistic town

00:10:04.150 --> 00:10:05.650
where every monument
and street was

00:10:05.650 --> 00:10:07.366
named for their predecessors.

00:10:07.366 --> 00:10:08.740
'Right, of course,'
said Kennedy.

00:10:08.740 --> 00:10:11.486
'We met you and your lovely
wife at Martin's Tavern.

00:10:11.486 --> 00:10:14.110
I just heard you're working with
Estes on the upcoming juvenile

00:10:14.110 --> 00:10:16.090
delinquency hearings.'

00:10:16.090 --> 00:10:17.830
Cohn choked on his drink.

00:10:17.830 --> 00:10:19.630
It turned out he was laughing.

00:10:19.630 --> 00:10:22.180
'You're part of those bullshit
comic book hearings,' he

00:10:22.180 --> 00:10:24.040
guffawed dramatically.

00:10:24.040 --> 00:10:26.560
Kennedy grinned and looked
at Charlie apologetically.

00:10:26.560 --> 00:10:28.090
Charlie was not
particularly amused.

00:10:28.090 --> 00:10:31.390
He'd had enough of Cohn's
abrasive company by now.

00:10:31.390 --> 00:10:33.910
'You were asking me about the
commie symps in this room,

00:10:33.910 --> 00:10:36.230
congressman,' Cohn said.

00:10:36.230 --> 00:10:38.830
'Well, they worry me more
than Wonder Woman does.'

00:10:38.830 --> 00:10:40.210
He took another
swig of his drink

00:10:40.210 --> 00:10:41.419
and stared out the window.

00:10:41.419 --> 00:10:43.960
'But none of them concern me as
much as the commie symps over

00:10:43.960 --> 00:10:46.660
there in that big white
building,' motioning with his

00:10:46.660 --> 00:10:48.250
chin toward the White House.

00:10:48.250 --> 00:10:50.740
'What must the world look
like from that address?

00:10:50.740 --> 00:10:52.710
It must look upside down.

00:10:52.710 --> 00:10:55.120
Goddamn Ike protects the
commies and screws with Senator

00:10:55.120 --> 00:10:56.270
McCarthy.'

00:10:56.270 --> 00:10:57.560
Cohn looked at Kennedy.

00:10:57.560 --> 00:10:59.920
'He's terrified Joe will
run for president, you know.

00:10:59.920 --> 00:11:02.320
Joe could beat him, too.'

00:11:02.320 --> 00:11:05.080
'Joe McCarthy could beat
President Eisenhower?' asked

00:11:05.080 --> 00:11:08.230
Charlie incredulously. 'Beat
the smartest general we've had

00:11:08.230 --> 00:11:09.520
since Sherman?'

00:11:09.520 --> 00:11:11.140
'Smart?' said Cohn.

00:11:11.140 --> 00:11:14.440
'MacArthur called Ike the
best clerk he ever had.'

00:11:14.440 --> 00:11:16.810
'And Ike said he studied
drama under General MacArthur

00:11:16.810 --> 00:11:18.250
for four years.'

00:11:18.250 --> 00:11:19.180
Kennedy chuckled.

00:11:19.180 --> 00:11:20.470
'Now, gentlemen.

00:11:20.470 --> 00:11:23.410
MacArthur-- MacArthur,'
said Charlie sarcastically,

00:11:23.410 --> 00:11:26.200
pretending to search the skies
for a reminder of the general,

00:11:26.200 --> 00:11:29.080
so ignominiously fired by
Truman three years earlier.

00:11:29.080 --> 00:11:30.610
'The name rings a bell.'

00:11:30.610 --> 00:11:33.590
'MacArthur's a great man,
a patriot,' said Cohn.

00:11:33.590 --> 00:11:36.290
'I'm sure you have a medal of
honor under your shirt there?'

00:11:36.290 --> 00:11:39.460
'No,' said Charlie,
'just some shrapnel.'

00:11:39.460 --> 00:11:41.200
He finished the
rest of his drink.

00:11:41.200 --> 00:11:44.830
'Nothing like your paper cuts
from the Battle of Torts 101.'

00:11:44.830 --> 00:11:46.930
An awkward silence
hung like a noose.

00:11:46.930 --> 00:11:49.120
Charlie had surprised even
himself with that one.

00:11:49.120 --> 00:11:51.070
Liquid courage, he supposed.

00:11:51.070 --> 00:11:52.630
Kennedy tried to
break the tension.

00:11:52.630 --> 00:11:55.330
'Why do you think Joe would
be a good president, Roy?'

00:11:55.330 --> 00:11:57.160
'If Joe were
president,' Cohn said,

00:11:57.160 --> 00:11:59.715
'the first thing he would do
would be to end the Cold War.

00:11:59.715 --> 00:12:01.840
He'd pick up the phone and
call Joe Stalin and say,

00:12:01.840 --> 00:12:02.924
this is Joe McCarthy.

00:12:02.924 --> 00:12:04.840
I'm coming over tomorrow
to talk about things.

00:12:04.840 --> 00:12:07.207
Meet me at the Moscow
airport at 1 o'clock.

00:12:07.207 --> 00:12:09.040
When he arrived in
Moscow, he would sit down

00:12:09.040 --> 00:12:10.660
with Stalin in a closed room.

00:12:10.660 --> 00:12:12.276
First, he'd tell a
couple dirty jokes.

00:12:12.276 --> 00:12:13.900
Then, he'd look Stalin
right in the eye

00:12:13.900 --> 00:12:16.720
and say, Joe, what do you want?

00:12:16.720 --> 00:12:18.220
And Stalin would tell him.

00:12:18.220 --> 00:12:20.904
They would talk man to man,
not like pansy diplomats.

00:12:20.904 --> 00:12:22.570
They'd find out what
each of them wanted

00:12:22.570 --> 00:12:24.220
and settle their differences.

00:12:24.220 --> 00:12:25.845
But when Joe left,
he'd tell Stalin,

00:12:25.845 --> 00:12:27.970
the first time I catch you
breaking this agreement,

00:12:27.970 --> 00:12:31.060
I'll blow you and your whole
goddamn country off the map.'

00:12:31.060 --> 00:12:32.560
Charlie turned to Kennedy.

00:12:32.560 --> 00:12:36.250
'He can't honestly believe
this rubbish, can't he?'"

00:12:36.250 --> 00:12:38.350
So one of the things
about that scene that I

00:12:38.350 --> 00:12:42.010
like is the entire paragraph
where Roy Cohn is explaining

00:12:42.010 --> 00:12:46.180
why he thinks Joe McCarthy
would be a great president

00:12:46.180 --> 00:12:49.540
is an actual paragraph, except
it wasn't said by Roy Cohn.

00:12:49.540 --> 00:12:53.170
It was said by Joe
McCarthy's campaign manager--

00:12:53.170 --> 00:12:55.240
a guy named Urban Van Susteren--

00:12:55.240 --> 00:12:58.510
who would go on to have a
daughter named Greta Van

00:12:58.510 --> 00:13:00.340
Susteren.

00:13:00.340 --> 00:13:04.840
And it really gets to the
fact that some of this stuff--

00:13:04.840 --> 00:13:08.050
the truth in the book-- is
often stranger than the fiction.

00:13:08.050 --> 00:13:12.040
That paragraph reminded
me so much of the pitch

00:13:12.040 --> 00:13:14.317
that we would hear
on the campaign trail

00:13:14.317 --> 00:13:16.150
about why Trump would
be a great negotiator.

00:13:16.150 --> 00:13:17.441
He'd go into a room with Putin.

00:13:17.441 --> 00:13:18.790
He'd do this-- blah, blah, blah.

00:13:18.790 --> 00:13:21.537
And you know, like I said,
history doesn't repeat itself,

00:13:21.537 --> 00:13:22.120
but it rhymes.

00:13:22.120 --> 00:13:23.650
And I heard a lot of rhyming.

00:13:23.650 --> 00:13:25.750
And one of the fun
things about this book--

00:13:25.750 --> 00:13:28.540
and it's actually one of the
reasons why I included about 10

00:13:28.540 --> 00:13:31.450
or 15 pages of endnotes
at the end of it--

00:13:31.450 --> 00:13:34.102
is because there's so many
weird details that are real,

00:13:34.102 --> 00:13:36.310
I wanted people to know that
I didn't make it all up.

00:13:36.310 --> 00:13:38.282
Like, a lot of it
actually happened.

00:13:38.282 --> 00:13:39.990
There's important
stuff, and then there's

00:13:39.990 --> 00:13:41.890
strange little color,
like when Eisenhower--

00:13:41.890 --> 00:13:46.150
I'm sorry, when McCarthy would
drink, which he did a lot,

00:13:46.150 --> 00:13:49.690
he would also eat
a stick of butter.

00:13:49.690 --> 00:13:52.930
He would just order a stick of
butter and eat it with a fork.

00:13:52.930 --> 00:13:55.667
And I thought it was so
strange, I put it in there.

00:13:55.667 --> 00:13:58.000
But I said, people are going
to think that, oh, it's too

00:13:58.000 --> 00:13:59.320
weird-- that I made that up.

00:13:59.320 --> 00:14:02.470
And then, so I put in a
whole endnote section,

00:14:02.470 --> 00:14:04.450
which is also probably
the researcher

00:14:04.450 --> 00:14:07.510
nerd in me showing
off a little, perhaps.

00:14:07.510 --> 00:14:09.550
Anyway, so that's
"The Hellfire Club."

00:14:09.550 --> 00:14:12.481
And it's doing OK.

00:14:12.481 --> 00:14:14.980
We're going to debut on "The
New York Times" bestseller list

00:14:14.980 --> 00:14:16.630
this Sunday at number three.

00:14:16.630 --> 00:14:20.322
And we've been selling
a lot of books.

00:14:20.322 --> 00:14:22.030
And I've been going
all over the country.

00:14:22.030 --> 00:14:23.404
And it's really
great to be here.

00:14:23.404 --> 00:14:26.000
And I'm happy to take
any questions you have.

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:27.910
And I recognize that
they might not all

00:14:27.910 --> 00:14:31.474
be about the book,
which is fine.

00:14:31.474 --> 00:14:33.015
But I do hope you
check out the book.

00:14:33.015 --> 00:14:34.870
So thank you so much

00:14:34.870 --> 00:14:37.270
[APPLAUSE]

00:14:40.526 --> 00:14:41.400
So should I sit here?

00:14:41.400 --> 00:14:42.185
OK, cool.

00:14:49.610 --> 00:14:52.000
SPEAKER: So I'll just
kick off the conversation.

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:54.320
I was really interested
in your choice

00:14:54.320 --> 00:14:58.340
to write a fiction novel at
this time in our history,

00:14:58.340 --> 00:14:59.720
when I think a
lot of journalists

00:14:59.720 --> 00:15:02.210
are publishing memoirs
right now, publishing

00:15:02.210 --> 00:15:03.740
a lot of non-fiction.

00:15:03.740 --> 00:15:06.020
And given the
parallels between what

00:15:06.020 --> 00:15:08.660
happened in the
McCarthy era and today,

00:15:08.660 --> 00:15:10.760
did you feel that fiction
was a really good way

00:15:10.760 --> 00:15:13.940
to sort of explore things
more allegorically as

00:15:13.940 --> 00:15:16.670
opposed to writing a
work of non-fiction?

00:15:16.670 --> 00:15:19.220
JAKE TAPPER: Yeah, well,
there are a few reasons,

00:15:19.220 --> 00:15:22.490
because we're complicated people
and we don't only do things

00:15:22.490 --> 00:15:24.020
for one reason, right?

00:15:24.020 --> 00:15:26.450
But one of them
was the last book

00:15:26.450 --> 00:15:28.490
I wrote was called
"The Outpost--

00:15:28.490 --> 00:15:31.880
An Untold Story of
American Valor."

00:15:31.880 --> 00:15:36.650
It was a true story about one
combat outpost in Afghanistan,

00:15:36.650 --> 00:15:39.890
and its whole 3.5 year history,
and then the deadliest battle

00:15:39.890 --> 00:15:42.200
for the US in 2009.

00:15:42.200 --> 00:15:46.530
And to be completely candid,
it was a very wrenching

00:15:46.530 --> 00:15:47.780
experience, writing that book.

00:15:47.780 --> 00:15:49.550
I did more than 200 interviews.

00:15:49.550 --> 00:15:52.190
I traveled to Afghanistan twice.

00:15:52.190 --> 00:15:53.840
I spent a lot of time
talking to people

00:15:53.840 --> 00:15:57.170
who had sacrificed a great deal,
including loved ones and limbs.

00:15:57.170 --> 00:15:58.842
And while certainly,
what I went through

00:15:58.842 --> 00:16:00.800
was nothing compared to
what they went through,

00:16:00.800 --> 00:16:02.690
it was very emotionally taxing.

00:16:02.690 --> 00:16:05.540
So I was looking for a
project that would be fun.

00:16:05.540 --> 00:16:08.700
That project was important,
but it wasn't fun.

00:16:08.700 --> 00:16:10.700
But then, yes, you're
absolutely onto something.

00:16:10.700 --> 00:16:13.530
I think that I was
able to make arguments

00:16:13.530 --> 00:16:18.440
I wanted to make about, not
just about indecency and lies--

00:16:18.440 --> 00:16:20.360
the kind that we're
experiencing now

00:16:20.360 --> 00:16:22.710
on a daily basis from
the White House--

00:16:22.710 --> 00:16:27.230
but also compromise,
also the importance

00:16:27.230 --> 00:16:29.160
of standing up for
what you believe in

00:16:29.160 --> 00:16:30.440
in an allegorical way.

00:16:30.440 --> 00:16:33.230
I think that if I had tried
to do it in a non-fiction way,

00:16:33.230 --> 00:16:35.040
it would not have worked.

00:16:35.040 --> 00:16:38.570
But doing it in a way that
was combined with a thriller

00:16:38.570 --> 00:16:42.710
and fun flight of
fancy elements--

00:16:42.710 --> 00:16:48.215
that that might make more
sense and be more effective.

00:16:48.215 --> 00:16:50.498
SPEAKER: Do folks in the
audience have questions?

00:16:54.490 --> 00:16:55.275
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:16:55.275 --> 00:16:57.990
So my question is
about lying, actually.

00:16:57.990 --> 00:16:59.790
And I appreciate that you--

00:16:59.790 --> 00:17:02.680
I've noticed you call out
people you're interviewing

00:17:02.680 --> 00:17:05.369
if they're obviously lying,
or if they're repeating lies,

00:17:05.369 --> 00:17:06.569
or that kind of thing.

00:17:06.569 --> 00:17:09.300
And I'm wondering if you
think, with your experience,

00:17:09.300 --> 00:17:11.010
that we may get back
to a point where

00:17:11.010 --> 00:17:14.172
people aren't lying as much,
or if this is sort of normal?

00:17:14.172 --> 00:17:15.630
And I'm also
interested in sort of,

00:17:15.630 --> 00:17:20.099
as a journalist, when you know
something is a lie, like just

00:17:20.099 --> 00:17:22.140
how are you striking that
balance when something

00:17:22.140 --> 00:17:23.520
is clearly a lie?

00:17:23.520 --> 00:17:25.680
JAKE TAPPER: So
everywhere I go, everybody

00:17:25.680 --> 00:17:26.760
wants to know whether
or not we're ever

00:17:26.760 --> 00:17:27.884
going to go back to normal.

00:17:27.884 --> 00:17:28.990
And I don't know.

00:17:28.990 --> 00:17:30.540
I hope so.

00:17:30.540 --> 00:17:33.780
I mean, right now, we're in
a period where in the last 24

00:17:33.780 --> 00:17:37.760
hours, somebody went
on "Fox Business News,"

00:17:37.760 --> 00:17:40.110
and attacked John McCain--

00:17:40.110 --> 00:17:43.010
called him Songbird
John, and basically

00:17:43.010 --> 00:17:45.349
smeared his war record.

00:17:45.349 --> 00:17:46.890
And then, somebody
at the White House

00:17:46.890 --> 00:17:49.850
was making fun of the
fact that he was dying.

00:17:49.850 --> 00:17:53.280
You know, I can't
even imagine that.

00:17:53.280 --> 00:17:56.040
I mean, I remember
covering the 2000 campaign

00:17:56.040 --> 00:17:58.530
when John McCain got
smeared in South Carolina,

00:17:58.530 --> 00:18:01.620
but at least that was
like shadowy groups

00:18:01.620 --> 00:18:03.720
without ties to--

00:18:03.720 --> 00:18:06.510
direct ties to George W. Bush
and his opponents at the time.

00:18:06.510 --> 00:18:08.370
This is like people
just saying things.

00:18:08.370 --> 00:18:10.864
So we're in a time of
lies and indecency.

00:18:10.864 --> 00:18:13.030
And I see them as part and
parcel of the same thing,

00:18:13.030 --> 00:18:16.260
because it all has to do with
we don't care about standards.

00:18:16.260 --> 00:18:18.100
And I hope we get back to it.

00:18:18.100 --> 00:18:19.410
I worry.

00:18:19.410 --> 00:18:20.880
I really do.

00:18:20.880 --> 00:18:25.524
In terms of calling out lies,
or untruths, or falsehoods,

00:18:25.524 --> 00:18:26.940
or whatever you
want to call them,

00:18:26.940 --> 00:18:28.920
I mean, a lie means
you know it's false

00:18:28.920 --> 00:18:31.320
and you're saying it anyway.

00:18:31.320 --> 00:18:35.610
And I try to be more
selective about the use of lie

00:18:35.610 --> 00:18:42.000
versus falsehood in terms
of what I can assert.

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:44.670
But if President Trump
says something wrong,

00:18:44.670 --> 00:18:46.620
and then after it's
been pointed out

00:18:46.620 --> 00:18:49.370
that it's wrong, he continues
to say it, at that point,

00:18:49.370 --> 00:18:50.640
I think it's a lie.

00:18:50.640 --> 00:18:54.259
Maybe the first time, he
misunderstood or he misspoke.

00:18:54.259 --> 00:18:55.800
And I just think we
just need to call

00:18:55.800 --> 00:18:58.860
these things what
they are because we

00:18:58.860 --> 00:18:59.850
can't normalize this.

00:18:59.850 --> 00:19:02.490
We can't normalize making
fun of the disabled,

00:19:02.490 --> 00:19:04.740
or making light of people's
drug and alcohol problems,

00:19:04.740 --> 00:19:07.080
or the demonization
of minorities.

00:19:07.080 --> 00:19:08.770
It's just not acceptable.

00:19:08.770 --> 00:19:11.700
And that's not to say that
he's wrong on immigration,

00:19:11.700 --> 00:19:14.467
or he's wrong on trade,
or he's wrong on--

00:19:14.467 --> 00:19:16.050
I mean, those are
issues and we should

00:19:16.050 --> 00:19:17.700
have those policy debates.

00:19:17.700 --> 00:19:20.490
But the indecency
and the lies just--

00:19:20.490 --> 00:19:25.061
if news anchors aren't willing
to say what they are, who is?

00:19:25.061 --> 00:19:25.560
Right?

00:19:25.560 --> 00:19:27.726
We're supposed to be the
arbiters of fact and truth.

00:19:27.726 --> 00:19:29.732
And if we can't say,
that's not true,

00:19:29.732 --> 00:19:31.440
then I don't know what
we're doing there.

00:19:34.954 --> 00:19:36.620
AUDIENCE: You might
have heard last week

00:19:36.620 --> 00:19:40.430
that there's a new Google
News app that was announced.

00:19:40.430 --> 00:19:44.160
Quite a few people in
this room worked on that

00:19:44.160 --> 00:19:45.500
and continue to work on it.

00:19:45.500 --> 00:19:48.700
If you had a lot
of people and a lot

00:19:48.700 --> 00:19:51.370
of resources in
terms of technology,

00:19:51.370 --> 00:19:52.772
what would you build?

00:19:52.772 --> 00:19:54.120
JAKE TAPPER: Oh, God.

00:19:54.120 --> 00:19:55.780
It's such a tough-- you know,
I was talking to [? Sanders ?]

00:19:55.780 --> 00:19:57.970
about this before, because
one of the things--

00:19:57.970 --> 00:20:01.090
I mean, I use Google
News all the time.

00:20:01.090 --> 00:20:01.990
I mean, all the time.

00:20:01.990 --> 00:20:04.840
I could not do my
job without Google.

00:20:04.840 --> 00:20:06.670
And in fact, by the
way, one of the reasons

00:20:06.670 --> 00:20:10.570
I set my book in 1954-- not the
main reason, by any stretch,

00:20:10.570 --> 00:20:13.290
but one of the reasons
why I set it in 1954--

00:20:13.290 --> 00:20:20.440
is because every plot of every
movie or book that we know

00:20:20.440 --> 00:20:24.097
and love inevitably would
become ruined if it was set now,

00:20:24.097 --> 00:20:25.930
because it's just like,
well, why didn't you

00:20:25.930 --> 00:20:30.250
just Google it and realize
that every city he's been to

00:20:30.250 --> 00:20:32.980
has had a rash of
serial murders?

00:20:32.980 --> 00:20:34.580
Why didn't you just call her?

00:20:34.580 --> 00:20:38.170
And then, I started noticing
that a lot of movies

00:20:38.170 --> 00:20:40.540
now, people are in the
middle of the desert

00:20:40.540 --> 00:20:42.460
and they don't have cell
service, because cell

00:20:42.460 --> 00:20:46.270
phones and Google ruin plots.

00:20:46.270 --> 00:20:47.530
So anyway, I use Google News.

00:20:47.530 --> 00:20:49.639
You know, I have to find
out more about this app.

00:20:49.639 --> 00:20:52.180
I mean, I've heard about it,
but I've been on this book tour,

00:20:52.180 --> 00:20:54.820
so I haven't had the
time to plunge in.

00:20:54.820 --> 00:20:56.680
I think one of the
problems-- and I

00:20:56.680 --> 00:20:58.060
don't know that
this is something

00:20:58.060 --> 00:21:00.310
that you guys can come up
with or what you can solve--

00:21:00.310 --> 00:21:02.860
but there's so much
fake news out there.

00:21:02.860 --> 00:21:04.820
There's so many lies out there.

00:21:04.820 --> 00:21:09.880
And it's not just by
truepundit.com or whatever.

00:21:09.880 --> 00:21:14.530
Some of them are by Breitbart
or agenda-driven publications.

00:21:14.530 --> 00:21:17.710
And I don't know how Facebook
or Google or anyone--

00:21:17.710 --> 00:21:19.720
how you make a decision
about what is news

00:21:19.720 --> 00:21:21.470
and what is not news.

00:21:21.470 --> 00:21:23.830
But since we're
talking theoretically,

00:21:23.830 --> 00:21:29.800
in my own perfect universe, I
would have some sort of method

00:21:29.800 --> 00:21:33.730
to help consumers, without
any sort of political agenda

00:21:33.730 --> 00:21:35.980
or political bias, a way
to discern what's real

00:21:35.980 --> 00:21:37.130
and what's not.

00:21:37.130 --> 00:21:39.310
But I don't think that
you guys can do that.

00:21:39.310 --> 00:21:40.820
This is in a perfect world.

00:21:40.820 --> 00:21:42.610
This is a utopian idea.

00:21:42.610 --> 00:21:44.967
And I recognize the
slippery slope of, well,

00:21:44.967 --> 00:21:47.050
if you say this about this
news organization, what

00:21:47.050 --> 00:21:48.280
about this news organization?

00:21:48.280 --> 00:21:51.126
Or if these people are purposely
wrong about this story, what

00:21:51.126 --> 00:21:53.500
about this time that "The New
York Times," or "NBC News,"

00:21:53.500 --> 00:21:55.880
or whatever got something
accidentally wrong, et cetera.

00:21:55.880 --> 00:21:59.470
So I realize it's a very
difficult challenge.

00:21:59.470 --> 00:22:01.497
And that probably didn't
answer your question.

00:22:01.497 --> 00:22:02.830
I'll think about it more though.

00:22:02.830 --> 00:22:03.580
AUDIENCE: That's pretty close.

00:22:03.580 --> 00:22:04.640
JAKE TAPPER: OK, thanks.

00:22:07.570 --> 00:22:10.030
AUDIENCE: Let's say,
10 years from now,

00:22:10.030 --> 00:22:12.575
you decide to write
a novel about today.

00:22:12.575 --> 00:22:14.950
I was wondering if you could
talk a little bit about what

00:22:14.950 --> 00:22:18.430
the protagonist would
be like in your novel.

00:22:18.430 --> 00:22:21.097
JAKE TAPPER: Well, I mean,
honestly, I don't think

00:22:21.097 --> 00:22:22.180
that "The Hellfire Club"--

00:22:22.180 --> 00:22:23.770
I mean, if you
read it, you'll see

00:22:23.770 --> 00:22:27.670
that there's a lot in the
book about the choices

00:22:27.670 --> 00:22:30.700
that people are facing
today, except it's just

00:22:30.700 --> 00:22:33.310
framed in the 1950s.

00:22:33.310 --> 00:22:36.580
If you read about
the 1950s, you'll

00:22:36.580 --> 00:22:40.039
see that there were
heroes at the time.

00:22:40.039 --> 00:22:42.580
One of my heroes-- now that I've
done research on this book--

00:22:42.580 --> 00:22:44.200
is a woman, Margaret
Chase Smith.

00:22:44.200 --> 00:22:45.542
She was a senator from Maine.

00:22:45.542 --> 00:22:47.500
First woman elected to
the House and the Senate

00:22:47.500 --> 00:22:49.150
in her own right.

00:22:49.150 --> 00:22:51.520
In 1950, she went to
the floor of the Senate

00:22:51.520 --> 00:22:55.330
and gave her declaration of
conscience speech, in which she

00:22:55.330 --> 00:22:58.870
condemned McCarthyism in 1950,
when he was just starting

00:22:58.870 --> 00:23:01.240
to become popular and powerful.

00:23:01.240 --> 00:23:03.110
Edward R. Murrow, who
is a hero of mine,

00:23:03.110 --> 00:23:05.710
he didn't go after
McCarthy until 1954.

00:23:05.710 --> 00:23:09.160
And the US Senate didn't censure
him till the end of 1954.

00:23:09.160 --> 00:23:12.070
So she was years ahead.

00:23:12.070 --> 00:23:15.700
One of the things when you read
about that era that you see

00:23:15.700 --> 00:23:18.040
is that there were a lot
of people who failed.

00:23:18.040 --> 00:23:19.810
The Kennedys failed,
quite frankly,

00:23:19.810 --> 00:23:22.720
and I'm a student
of the Kennedys.

00:23:22.720 --> 00:23:25.330
But Robert Kennedy was the
chief democratic counsel

00:23:25.330 --> 00:23:26.680
on the McCarthy committee.

00:23:26.680 --> 00:23:28.299
John F. Kennedy was
pretty AWOL when

00:23:28.299 --> 00:23:29.590
it came to condemning McCarthy.

00:23:32.140 --> 00:23:36.010
More importantly, McCarthy's
fellow Republicans failed.

00:23:36.010 --> 00:23:39.220
Senator Bob Taft, who ran
for president in 1952,

00:23:39.220 --> 00:23:42.400
lost to Eisenhower-- lost
the nomination to Eisenhower.

00:23:42.400 --> 00:23:44.590
But the Senate went
into Republican hands,

00:23:44.590 --> 00:23:46.630
and Taft became the
majority leader.

00:23:46.630 --> 00:23:49.120
I'm sure that Senator Taft
thought that his agenda--

00:23:49.120 --> 00:23:52.450
his legacy would be that he's
Mr. Conservative, that he stood

00:23:52.450 --> 00:23:53.860
up for these
conservative values,

00:23:53.860 --> 00:23:55.984
that he represented something
important in American

00:23:55.984 --> 00:23:58.400
foreign policy and
American domestic policy.

00:23:58.400 --> 00:24:02.500
But at the end of the day,
he died suddenly in 1953.

00:24:02.500 --> 00:24:06.130
And a big part of his legacy is
he didn't stand up to McCarthy.

00:24:06.130 --> 00:24:07.930
And if I were a
member of Congress,

00:24:07.930 --> 00:24:10.980
I would think about Bob
Taft every day of the year--

00:24:10.980 --> 00:24:13.010
every day-- and think--

00:24:13.010 --> 00:24:15.010
we all like to think that
our legacies are going

00:24:15.010 --> 00:24:17.343
to be like our achievements,
but the truth of the matter

00:24:17.343 --> 00:24:19.450
is our legacy and
how we're remembered

00:24:19.450 --> 00:24:23.980
is often dictated
by the moral choices

00:24:23.980 --> 00:24:26.140
that we make, or fail to make.

00:24:26.140 --> 00:24:29.560
And so I don't think I need to
write a book about the Trump

00:24:29.560 --> 00:24:35.611
era because I think what I've
written is resonant enough.

00:24:35.611 --> 00:24:36.360
But you know what?

00:24:36.360 --> 00:24:38.040
Maybe my son will
write it in 50 years,

00:24:38.040 --> 00:24:40.410
and you can say that
it was your idea

00:24:40.410 --> 00:24:43.350
and try to get a
share of the profits.

00:24:43.350 --> 00:24:45.750
SPEAKER: I want to take one
of our online questions now.

00:24:45.750 --> 00:24:48.090
This one is on immigration.

00:24:48.090 --> 00:24:50.790
"I feel media always
tends to discuss more

00:24:50.790 --> 00:24:54.272
about undocumented immigrants,
with whom I sympathize,

00:24:54.272 --> 00:24:55.980
and ignore the plight
of legal immigrants

00:24:55.980 --> 00:24:57.990
who have to get through
hellish restrictions.

00:24:57.990 --> 00:25:00.630
Do you see a change in future
where legal immigrants would

00:25:00.630 --> 00:25:03.000
be considered for discussion
in media and elsewhere?"

00:25:03.000 --> 00:25:04.708
JAKE TAPPER: Yeah,
it's a great question.

00:25:04.708 --> 00:25:06.870
I mean, I think the reason
that the media focuses

00:25:06.870 --> 00:25:09.570
on illegal immigrants, or
undocumented immigrants,

00:25:09.570 --> 00:25:14.225
is because they are the ones
that are being threatened-- you

00:25:14.225 --> 00:25:16.350
know, rounded up in ICE
raids, and being threatened

00:25:16.350 --> 00:25:18.180
with expulsion, et cetera.

00:25:18.180 --> 00:25:20.400
We do have legal
immigrants on our shows

00:25:20.400 --> 00:25:22.590
all the time, not because
they're legal immigrants,

00:25:22.590 --> 00:25:24.660
but because they just happen
to be incredibly talented

00:25:24.660 --> 00:25:26.826
and it turns out they're
legal immigrants-- like Ana

00:25:26.826 --> 00:25:30.210
Navarro, who is from
Nicaragua, is a good example.

00:25:30.210 --> 00:25:34.170
But I think the
debate is largely

00:25:34.170 --> 00:25:36.540
about illegal immigration.

00:25:36.540 --> 00:25:41.670
Although the immigration
bill that Cotton and Perdue

00:25:41.670 --> 00:25:46.800
introduced-- which would have a
big effect on legal immigration

00:25:46.800 --> 00:25:49.796
if that bill ever were to
become seriously considered,

00:25:49.796 --> 00:25:51.420
which I don't think
it would as of now,

00:25:51.420 --> 00:25:53.809
not with this Senate and the
Democrats able to block it--

00:25:53.809 --> 00:25:56.100
I think there would be a lot
more discussion and debate

00:25:56.100 --> 00:25:58.440
about legal immigration.

00:25:58.440 --> 00:26:01.170
Unfortunately, we
have to make choices.

00:26:01.170 --> 00:26:05.880
And the people in the media
tend to go to the bigger story

00:26:05.880 --> 00:26:08.160
and can't always
focus on everything.

00:26:10.860 --> 00:26:14.370
AUDIENCE: So sort of related to
your comments about fake news,

00:26:14.370 --> 00:26:17.979
a lot of people often
just receive news

00:26:17.979 --> 00:26:19.770
from a single source
or from their friends,

00:26:19.770 --> 00:26:20.770
which may not be fake.

00:26:20.770 --> 00:26:23.103
It might be good news, but
it might also be consistently

00:26:23.103 --> 00:26:25.650
from one point of view.

00:26:25.650 --> 00:26:28.530
Do you have any
suggestions for how

00:26:28.530 --> 00:26:32.070
people could be broken out
of their ideological echo

00:26:32.070 --> 00:26:32.642
chambers?

00:26:32.642 --> 00:26:34.100
JAKE TAPPER: Yeah,
and I'm a huge--

00:26:34.100 --> 00:26:35.540
I follow more than--

00:26:35.540 --> 00:26:37.170
not to bring up a
competitor-- but I

00:26:37.170 --> 00:26:39.270
follow more than 5,000
people on Twitter.

00:26:39.270 --> 00:26:41.010
And one of the great
things about it

00:26:41.010 --> 00:26:44.340
is I try to get as many
divergent viewpoints as

00:26:44.340 --> 00:26:44.910
possible.

00:26:44.910 --> 00:26:46.714
And I completely agree with--

00:26:46.714 --> 00:26:48.630
look, I was the kid in
high school and college

00:26:48.630 --> 00:26:49.838
that would go to the library.

00:26:49.838 --> 00:26:51.570
And I would read "The
Nation," and then I

00:26:51.570 --> 00:26:53.910
would read the
"National Review."

00:26:53.910 --> 00:26:57.630
I was always trying to get news
from different perspectives.

00:26:57.630 --> 00:27:00.299
And my friends in DC--

00:27:00.299 --> 00:27:02.340
some of them are very,
very liberal, some of them

00:27:02.340 --> 00:27:04.380
are very, very conservative.

00:27:04.380 --> 00:27:09.990
And as somebody who is generally
fairly politically agnostic

00:27:09.990 --> 00:27:15.010
in my personal views, which
is actually kind of a relief,

00:27:15.010 --> 00:27:18.150
it's a pleasure for me
to try to open my eyes

00:27:18.150 --> 00:27:20.190
and see how the world
looks to everyone.

00:27:20.190 --> 00:27:24.660
Now, sometimes, the world looks
to some people rooted like it's

00:27:24.660 --> 00:27:26.070
not actually this world.

00:27:26.070 --> 00:27:27.810
It's actually some
other world where

00:27:27.810 --> 00:27:30.060
there's a whole other set
of facts, that on this world

00:27:30.060 --> 00:27:31.890
are actually not true.

00:27:31.890 --> 00:27:34.920
So I tend to avoid those
websites and those channels.

00:27:34.920 --> 00:27:39.330
But I think that it's-- and I'm
giving a commencement address

00:27:39.330 --> 00:27:40.620
at UMass Amherst later today.

00:27:40.620 --> 00:27:42.453
And one of the things
I'm going to be saying

00:27:42.453 --> 00:27:45.780
is expose yourself to as
many different points of view

00:27:45.780 --> 00:27:49.230
as possible because that's
how you enrich your knowledge.

00:27:49.230 --> 00:27:52.140
And not just in terms of
liberal versus conservative,

00:27:52.140 --> 00:27:55.890
but also in terms of
military versus nonmilitary,

00:27:55.890 --> 00:28:00.150
or what does the world
look like from Yemen,

00:28:00.150 --> 00:28:02.550
what does the world look
like from the point of view

00:28:02.550 --> 00:28:05.400
of somebody who is deeply
religious-- whether Baptist,

00:28:05.400 --> 00:28:06.450
or Muslim, or Jewish.

00:28:06.450 --> 00:28:09.190
I mean, to expose yourself to
all different points of view,

00:28:09.190 --> 00:28:10.300
I think, is so important.

00:28:10.300 --> 00:28:13.230
It's a big part of what
you guys do, I know.

00:28:13.230 --> 00:28:15.480
And it's a big part
of what I do too.

