00:29:30.100 --> 00:29:31.230
I can't explain it.

00:29:31.230 --> 00:29:33.880
AUDIENCE: Well, it was a
little different before 2004.

00:29:33.880 --> 00:29:34.861
JAKE TAPPER: Yeah.

00:29:34.861 --> 00:29:36.110
AUDIENCE: But my question is--

00:29:36.110 --> 00:29:37.610
so you talked a
little bit about how

00:29:37.610 --> 00:29:39.820
the DC you write
about in the book

00:29:39.820 --> 00:29:42.940
is maybe not that different
than the DC we see today.

00:29:42.940 --> 00:29:44.830
And I think a lot
of us, regardless

00:29:44.830 --> 00:29:47.380
of political leaning,
feel pretty fed up,

00:29:47.380 --> 00:29:51.497
and in some ways, at a little
bit of a loss about what to do.

00:29:51.497 --> 00:29:53.080
And we hear a lot
of talk about, well,

00:29:53.080 --> 00:29:54.640
if you really want to
make a difference, run

00:29:54.640 --> 00:29:55.600
for local office.

00:29:55.600 --> 00:29:56.530
And that makes sense.

00:29:56.530 --> 00:29:58.404
And some people are in
a position to do that,

00:29:58.404 --> 00:30:00.452
and many of us maybe are not.

00:30:00.452 --> 00:30:02.410
So I guess I'm wondering
if you have one or two

00:30:02.410 --> 00:30:04.451
pieces of advice-- sort
of the first things you'd

00:30:04.451 --> 00:30:06.820
say to an everyday
engaged citizen about what

00:30:06.820 --> 00:30:08.555
steps to take.

00:30:08.555 --> 00:30:09.430
JAKE TAPPER: Wow, OK.

00:30:09.430 --> 00:30:12.910
So that's a really
good question.

00:30:12.910 --> 00:30:16.210
The truth of the matter is, is
that the best thing you can do

00:30:16.210 --> 00:30:18.910
is support candidates
that you believe in.

00:30:18.910 --> 00:30:24.220
And if it's local candidates,
then you can knock on doors

00:30:24.220 --> 00:30:27.340
and make phone calls.

00:30:27.340 --> 00:30:33.746
And if it's candidates in other
states, you can send money.

00:30:33.746 --> 00:30:37.120
Or also there are ways to
either travel to knock on doors

00:30:37.120 --> 00:30:40.270
or make phone calls, also.

00:30:40.270 --> 00:30:42.880
Although, you know, generally
those kinds of things

00:30:42.880 --> 00:30:46.000
are better coming from in state.

00:30:46.000 --> 00:30:50.170
But, you know, I
think that Washington

00:30:50.170 --> 00:30:52.780
is better in some ways
than it was in the 1950s.

00:30:52.780 --> 00:30:55.660
Because of the post-Watergate
reforms, we know more.

00:30:55.660 --> 00:30:57.790
Believe it or not, the
media is much better now

00:30:57.790 --> 00:30:59.590
than the media was in the 1950s.

00:30:59.590 --> 00:31:02.740
The media covered up all sorts
of stuff for people in power.

00:31:02.740 --> 00:31:03.612
And we know things.

00:31:03.612 --> 00:31:05.320
Somebody asked me the
other day about how

00:31:05.320 --> 00:31:09.910
would a journalist in the
1950s cover Scott Pruitt.

00:31:09.910 --> 00:31:12.040
We wouldn't even know
about Scott Pruitt.

00:31:12.040 --> 00:31:14.230
We wouldn't know
any of that stuff.

00:31:14.230 --> 00:31:17.500
And there wouldn't be reporters
covering it as aggressively.

00:31:17.500 --> 00:31:19.660
If you go back and
read newspapers from

00:31:19.660 --> 00:31:21.962
the '50s-- and I
did for this book--

00:31:21.962 --> 00:31:23.920
there was a lot of great
journalism being done,

00:31:23.920 --> 00:31:26.050
but it is much more
aggressive today.

00:31:26.050 --> 00:31:28.030
So things, I think, are
better in many ways.

00:31:28.030 --> 00:31:30.070
There's a lot more money today.

00:31:30.070 --> 00:31:32.300
And that makes it worse.

00:31:32.300 --> 00:31:36.190
But on balance, I would say
we're probably a little better

00:31:36.190 --> 00:31:36.890
off.

00:31:36.890 --> 00:31:39.490
But I honestly think that the
best thing that people can do

00:31:39.490 --> 00:31:44.290
is find candidates
who you believe in.

00:31:44.290 --> 00:31:47.770
And also, I don't think--

00:31:47.770 --> 00:31:49.270
I mean, if you're
a Democrat, great.

00:31:49.270 --> 00:31:50.920
If you're a Republican, great.

00:31:50.920 --> 00:31:54.910
But I think that people should
scratch beneath the surface

00:31:54.910 --> 00:31:56.980
beyond just party labels.

00:31:56.980 --> 00:32:00.640
It's important that there be
reformers in both parties.

00:32:00.640 --> 00:32:02.380
It's important that
there be people

00:32:02.380 --> 00:32:09.390
in both parties who are willing
to stand up for certain values.

00:32:09.390 --> 00:32:11.219
There's a guy named--

00:32:11.219 --> 00:32:13.510
well, I probably shouldn't
name individual politicians,

00:32:13.510 --> 00:32:16.360
but let me just say that there
are Democrats and Republicans

00:32:16.360 --> 00:32:20.260
in Washington who I
see legitimately raging

00:32:20.260 --> 00:32:22.720
against the machine and
really actually trying

00:32:22.720 --> 00:32:25.430
to do good and stand
up for what is right.

00:32:25.430 --> 00:32:28.720
And I think it's important
to have both parties have

00:32:28.720 --> 00:32:30.770
that kind of pressure.

00:32:30.770 --> 00:32:34.090
So if you are not necessarily
the most partisan person

00:32:34.090 --> 00:32:37.401
in the world, I would argue,
look at the other party

00:32:37.401 --> 00:32:39.400
and see if there are
people from the other party

00:32:39.400 --> 00:32:41.320
that you can support
in the primary.

00:32:41.320 --> 00:32:45.214
So even if-- and also
there are certain districts

00:32:45.214 --> 00:32:46.880
that are never going
to elect a Democrat

00:32:46.880 --> 00:32:47.980
and certain districts
that are never

00:32:47.980 --> 00:32:49.450
going to elect a Republican.

00:32:49.450 --> 00:32:52.000
There's nothing wrong
with, theoretically,

00:32:52.000 --> 00:32:54.520
finding the best person from
the party that's definitely

00:32:54.520 --> 00:32:56.781
going to win and
supporting that party

00:32:56.781 --> 00:32:58.780
and supporting that person,
even if you disagree

00:32:58.780 --> 00:33:01.470
with them on issue x, y, and z.

00:33:01.470 --> 00:33:02.391
That's just my view.

00:33:02.391 --> 00:33:03.640
Look, it's easy for me to say.

00:33:03.640 --> 00:33:06.160
I don't give money to anybody
because I'm a journalist.

00:33:06.160 --> 00:33:11.320
But I mean, I just think
that a lot of times

00:33:11.320 --> 00:33:13.690
I don't look at the world and--

00:33:13.690 --> 00:33:17.800
people who live in Washington
and political journalists

00:33:17.800 --> 00:33:19.820
see that partisanship
is important

00:33:19.820 --> 00:33:21.070
and the parties are different.

00:33:21.070 --> 00:33:22.750
And I'm not disputing
any of that,

00:33:22.750 --> 00:33:25.270
but there are also other
ways to split up the town.

00:33:25.270 --> 00:33:27.550
And one of them is people
who want to reform it

00:33:27.550 --> 00:33:31.510
and people who like how
it is, because the status

00:33:31.510 --> 00:33:33.494
quo is fine with them.

00:33:33.494 --> 00:33:35.410
Can I say one other thing
about your question?

00:33:35.410 --> 00:33:41.110
Which is, it is tougher to
challenge yourself and get out

00:33:41.110 --> 00:33:42.910
of your ideological--
not you-- but get out

00:33:42.910 --> 00:33:46.060
of one's ideological bubble.

00:33:46.060 --> 00:33:49.480
Right now, we are in a
period where people go home

00:33:49.480 --> 00:33:52.330
and they put on their team
jerseys and watch cable news.

00:33:52.330 --> 00:33:55.660
And they want to have
their beliefs reaffirmed.

00:33:55.660 --> 00:33:57.640
And I see things
on both of our--

00:33:57.640 --> 00:33:59.990
look, I'm biased
because I'm with CNN,

00:33:59.990 --> 00:34:02.410
but I see things on
both channels that

00:34:02.410 --> 00:34:05.680
are our main competitors,
Fox and MS, that I think,

00:34:05.680 --> 00:34:08.080
that's really not
telling the whole story.

00:34:08.080 --> 00:34:10.810
Sometimes I watch MSNBC
or see something on MSNBC

00:34:10.810 --> 00:34:13.609
and I think, boy,
they make it sound

00:34:13.609 --> 00:34:15.400
like President Trump's
about to be arrested

00:34:15.400 --> 00:34:16.840
in like the next five minutes.

00:34:16.840 --> 00:34:21.120
And then on Fox,
there's no Russian--

00:34:21.120 --> 00:34:23.120
what Russian investigation?

00:34:23.120 --> 00:34:25.840
So I mean, I think breaking
free of those bubbles

00:34:25.840 --> 00:34:29.610
is very important, even though
it's more difficult to do that.

00:34:29.610 --> 00:34:31.150
Sorry.

00:34:31.150 --> 00:34:31.960
AUDIENCE: Great.

00:34:31.960 --> 00:34:32.929
Thanks for being here.

00:34:32.929 --> 00:34:35.320
So I wanted to talk a little bit
about the kind of terminology

00:34:35.320 --> 00:34:35.820
that we use.

00:34:35.820 --> 00:34:38.770
Like, for instance,
I'm a big fan

00:34:38.770 --> 00:34:41.860
of liberal democratic
values, but more so

00:34:41.860 --> 00:34:44.739
in the Thomas Jefferson sense
than the Elizabeth Warren

00:34:44.739 --> 00:34:46.510
sense.

00:34:46.510 --> 00:34:52.300
So as far as lower case
liberal democratic principles,

00:34:52.300 --> 00:34:57.580
what do you see the media's
role as in promoting, defending,

00:34:57.580 --> 00:34:59.020
championing those
values, or being

00:34:59.020 --> 00:35:02.380
neutral about them relative
to maybe illiberal values

00:35:02.380 --> 00:35:03.310
or undemocratic?

00:35:03.310 --> 00:35:05.740
JAKE TAPPER: Well,
why don't you tell us?

00:35:05.740 --> 00:35:10.030
How would you define lowercase
l liberal and lowercase d

00:35:10.030 --> 00:35:11.170
democratic values?

00:35:11.170 --> 00:35:11.890
How would you?

00:35:11.890 --> 00:35:12.920
AUDIENCE: Sure.

00:35:12.920 --> 00:35:15.190
So I'll borrow the
definition from Yascha Mounk,

00:35:15.190 --> 00:35:18.790
who was here a couple months
ago giving a similar talk.

00:35:18.790 --> 00:35:22.920
Which is, liberalism in the
sense of civil liberties,

00:35:22.920 --> 00:35:28.000
standing up for the voice and
the rights of minority groups

00:35:28.000 --> 00:35:32.230
or marginalized
groups in society,

00:35:32.230 --> 00:35:37.150
and democracy being the will
of the people translated

00:35:37.150 --> 00:35:40.810
through some process or
representation in government.

00:35:40.810 --> 00:35:42.740
And these can be at odds, right?

00:35:42.740 --> 00:35:45.460
But for instance, if the
majority of the people

00:35:45.460 --> 00:35:47.770
decide that, yes, we need
to strip this minority

00:35:47.770 --> 00:35:50.140
group of certain rights
or certain voting

00:35:50.140 --> 00:35:53.950
rights or their voice,
there's some tension there.

00:35:53.950 --> 00:35:56.450
But together, it seems like
that's the magical package,

00:35:56.450 --> 00:35:57.950
that when America
throughout history

00:35:57.950 --> 00:36:01.680
is operating at its best, we
find a good balance of that.

00:36:01.680 --> 00:36:04.820
But at times, we get off balance
and off kilter about that.

00:36:04.820 --> 00:36:07.540
So I'm curious about those
combined values which

00:36:07.540 --> 00:36:10.510
don't always
naturally go together,

00:36:10.510 --> 00:36:14.680
do you see the media as having
a role with those values

00:36:14.680 --> 00:36:18.040
and promoting them or being
more neutral about them,

00:36:18.040 --> 00:36:21.160
like the media ideally should
be neutral about partisan

00:36:21.160 --> 00:36:22.910
political policy issues?

00:36:22.910 --> 00:36:23.980
JAKE TAPPER: Yeah, that's
a challenging question.

00:36:23.980 --> 00:36:25.030
I mean, I think,
first of all, one

00:36:25.030 --> 00:36:27.113
of the things that's at
the heart of your question

00:36:27.113 --> 00:36:30.640
is the idea that we should
be covering individual issues

00:36:30.640 --> 00:36:33.220
on their merits and not--

00:36:33.220 --> 00:36:35.945
without the partisan divide
necessarily as the only prism

00:36:35.945 --> 00:36:36.820
through which we see.

00:36:36.820 --> 00:36:38.194
I mean, so for
instance, if we're

00:36:38.194 --> 00:36:44.050
talking about NSA
wiretapping, or drone strikes,

00:36:44.050 --> 00:36:45.850
or whatever, we
should just be talking

00:36:45.850 --> 00:36:47.590
about that in terms
of the efficacy

00:36:47.590 --> 00:36:49.834
and the morality of it.

00:36:49.834 --> 00:36:51.250
And I think the
best way we can do

00:36:51.250 --> 00:36:55.690
that is by having intellectually
honest guests to discuss them.

00:36:55.690 --> 00:36:58.529
And sometimes it's, in
Washington, not always

00:36:58.529 --> 00:37:00.070
the easiest thing
in the world to do,

00:37:00.070 --> 00:37:02.486
because people tend to see
things through partisan lenses.

00:37:02.486 --> 00:37:06.754
But for instance, Senator
Chris Murphy of Connecticut,

00:37:06.754 --> 00:37:08.170
who is a pretty
partisan Democrat,

00:37:08.170 --> 00:37:10.480
but he was very critical
of the Obama administration

00:37:10.480 --> 00:37:12.494
for its role in--

00:37:12.494 --> 00:37:14.410
this is not a domestic
issue, but for its role

00:37:14.410 --> 00:37:20.410
in the war in Yemen, the
proxy war between Saudi Arabia

00:37:20.410 --> 00:37:22.450
and Iran that's going
on in Yemen right now.

00:37:22.450 --> 00:37:25.540
And having him on-- whenever
there's somebody who is just

00:37:25.540 --> 00:37:29.080
refreshingly candid, and honest,
and open about a debate about

00:37:29.080 --> 00:37:30.910
a principle--

00:37:30.910 --> 00:37:32.590
Senator Tim Kaine
was like that when

00:37:32.590 --> 00:37:35.650
it came to the authorization
for use of military force.

00:37:35.650 --> 00:37:37.912
I think it's just important
to run to those voices

00:37:37.912 --> 00:37:39.370
so that people can
see these issues

00:37:39.370 --> 00:37:41.440
through non-partisan lenses.

00:37:41.440 --> 00:37:43.780
In terms of the
positions we take,

00:37:43.780 --> 00:37:46.480
I don't know that it's my job
to say the United States should

00:37:46.480 --> 00:37:47.510
not be doing this.

00:37:47.510 --> 00:37:48.550
The United States should
not be doing that.

00:37:48.550 --> 00:37:50.650
I think that there are
certain lines we can draw,

00:37:50.650 --> 00:37:52.900
but really it's much
more my job to have

00:37:52.900 --> 00:37:54.775
on people to have
discussions about these

00:37:54.775 --> 00:37:58.210
and to make sure that these
discussions are rooted in facts

00:37:58.210 --> 00:38:04.660
and truth, and where people
can make their arguments one

00:38:04.660 --> 00:38:05.720
way or the other.

00:38:05.720 --> 00:38:07.750
I don't necessarily--
unless it's stark,

00:38:07.750 --> 00:38:10.880
I don't think it helps
the viewer for me to say,

00:38:10.880 --> 00:38:12.530
well, this is unconstitutional.

00:38:12.530 --> 00:38:14.992
That's not for me to say if
there's a debate about it.

00:38:14.992 --> 00:38:15.700
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:38:15.700 --> 00:38:17.804
JAKE TAPPER: Thanks.

00:38:17.804 --> 00:38:18.970
AUDIENCE: Thanks for coming.

00:38:18.970 --> 00:38:21.760
So getting back to the parallels
between Trump and McCarthy,

00:38:21.760 --> 00:38:24.820
McCarthy eventually reached
a point where he went too far

00:38:24.820 --> 00:38:27.550
and the party abandoned
him and he was censured.

00:38:27.550 --> 00:38:30.340
Can you foresee any
sort of similar scenario

00:38:30.340 --> 00:38:32.380
where something similar
happens with Trump,

00:38:32.380 --> 00:38:34.570
or do you think it's as
straightforward as, as long

00:38:34.570 --> 00:38:36.370
as the base supports
him the Republican

00:38:36.370 --> 00:38:39.294
Party is going to fall in line?

00:38:39.294 --> 00:38:40.960
JAKE TAPPER: It's a
lot more complicated

00:38:40.960 --> 00:38:42.985
than that, because first of
all, he's the president and not

00:38:42.985 --> 00:38:43.960
a Wisconsin senator.

00:38:43.960 --> 00:38:46.450
Second of all,
he's signing bills

00:38:46.450 --> 00:38:48.190
that the Republicans
want him to sign,

00:38:48.190 --> 00:38:52.270
and he's doing things that
some of them, I think,

00:38:52.270 --> 00:38:53.470
have his support.

00:38:53.470 --> 00:38:56.200
If he succeeds to
any degree in North

00:38:56.200 --> 00:38:59.660
Korea and the Korean peninsula,
that will be a great thing.

00:38:59.660 --> 00:39:03.434
But in terms of just the decency
and the lies, I don't know.

00:39:03.434 --> 00:39:05.350
And if I've learned
anything about predictions

00:39:05.350 --> 00:39:06.730
with Donald Trump, it's
don't make predictions

00:39:06.730 --> 00:39:07.810
about Donald Trump.

00:39:07.810 --> 00:39:11.410
But I do wonder,
if he were to fire

00:39:11.410 --> 00:39:13.330
Mueller, what would happen?

00:39:13.330 --> 00:39:15.050
Would that be a bridge too far?

00:39:15.050 --> 00:39:18.550
I feel as though Speaker
Ryan and Leader McConnell

00:39:18.550 --> 00:39:21.072
have made it clear,
privately and publicly,

00:39:21.072 --> 00:39:22.780
that they don't think
that should happen.

00:39:22.780 --> 00:39:25.714
I don't know what they
are willing to tolerate.

00:39:25.714 --> 00:39:27.880
And I don't know what
Republican members of Congress

00:39:27.880 --> 00:39:30.280
are willing to tolerate.

00:39:30.280 --> 00:39:33.760
Having lived through and
covered the Clinton years,

00:39:33.760 --> 00:39:35.464
I find it unimaginable.

00:39:35.464 --> 00:39:36.380
I mean, if President--

00:39:36.380 --> 00:39:38.320
I guess he couldn't have
fired Ken Starr because there

00:39:38.320 --> 00:39:40.111
was an independent
counsel law at the time,

00:39:40.111 --> 00:39:45.340
but behavior is being
tolerated now by Republicans

00:39:45.340 --> 00:39:47.500
that they never would
have tolerated before.

00:39:47.500 --> 00:39:51.550
And in fact, every
day it's just a

00:39:51.550 --> 00:39:53.140
here's what Rudy
Giuliani says now

00:39:53.140 --> 00:39:54.460
and here's what he
said 20 years ago,

00:39:54.460 --> 00:39:55.780
and it was the same
exact situation

00:39:55.780 --> 00:39:56.870
except it was Bill Clinton.

00:39:56.870 --> 00:39:58.330
Here's what Mike Pence
says now, except here's

00:39:58.330 --> 00:40:01.030
what he said two years ago
when it was Hillary Clinton.

00:40:01.030 --> 00:40:03.220
So the hypocrisy doesn't
seem to bother people

00:40:03.220 --> 00:40:06.020
very much anymore.

00:40:06.020 --> 00:40:07.360
I don't know.

00:40:07.360 --> 00:40:07.960
I don't know.

00:40:07.960 --> 00:40:09.310
I don't know how
much farther we're

00:40:09.310 --> 00:40:11.530
going to be tested as a
nation, in terms of the checks

00:40:11.530 --> 00:40:12.071
and balances.

00:40:12.071 --> 00:40:18.970
So far everything, the American
institutions and the separation

00:40:18.970 --> 00:40:21.220
of powers are still there.

00:40:21.220 --> 00:40:23.560
Mueller is still investigating.

00:40:23.560 --> 00:40:26.020
I don't know.

00:40:26.020 --> 00:40:27.690
If I had to pick
a bridge too far,

00:40:27.690 --> 00:40:29.740
it would be possibly
firing Mueller,

00:40:29.740 --> 00:40:31.090
but I honestly don't know.

00:40:31.090 --> 00:40:32.730
And if you go back and look at--

00:40:32.730 --> 00:40:36.280
I mean, the Senate tolerated
a lot from Joe McCarthy.

00:40:36.280 --> 00:40:36.960
A lot.

00:40:36.960 --> 00:40:42.010
And you go back, he smeared
senators in the late '40s.

00:40:42.010 --> 00:40:44.350
I mean, there's
this bizarre-- it's

00:40:44.350 --> 00:40:46.610
mentioned briefly in the book.

00:40:46.610 --> 00:40:50.500
There's this bizarre period in
American history, where there

00:40:50.500 --> 00:40:55.210
was a massacre committed by
Nazis towards the end of World

00:40:55.210 --> 00:40:56.330
War II.

00:40:56.330 --> 00:41:00.490
And then a lot of those
Nazis were captured,

00:41:00.490 --> 00:41:03.820
and they went to a prisoner
of war camp in New Jersey.

00:41:03.820 --> 00:41:07.780
And interrogators, American
military interrogators,

00:41:07.780 --> 00:41:12.360
were accused of being
too tough on these Nazis.

00:41:12.360 --> 00:41:14.110
They weren't torturing
them, but they were

00:41:14.110 --> 00:41:15.880
accused of mistreating them.

00:41:15.880 --> 00:41:18.770
And at the time
in the late '40s,

00:41:18.770 --> 00:41:22.870
there was a big movement by
German Americans to whitewash

00:41:22.870 --> 00:41:25.300
what had happened
in World War II.

00:41:25.300 --> 00:41:27.820
And McCarthy was part of that.

00:41:27.820 --> 00:41:30.850
And he took over this committee
he wasn't even a member of,

00:41:30.850 --> 00:41:33.220
that was investigating
the alleged mistreatment

00:41:33.220 --> 00:41:36.910
of these Nazis, and basically
smeared the chairman, who

00:41:36.910 --> 00:41:39.280
ended up retiring.

00:41:39.280 --> 00:41:42.290
And I have a character in the
book saying something like,

00:41:42.290 --> 00:41:45.340
"Oh, I thought we'd all come
to our conclusions about Nazis

00:41:45.340 --> 00:41:51.940
already," which was something
else that I added post-2016.

00:41:51.940 --> 00:41:55.840
So my only point is, the
US Senate tolerated a lot.

00:41:55.840 --> 00:41:57.610
He smeared war heroes.

00:41:57.610 --> 00:41:58.630
He smeared US senators.

00:41:58.630 --> 00:42:00.650
He smeared US senators.

00:42:00.650 --> 00:42:05.050
It was only after the
Army-McCarthy hearings

00:42:05.050 --> 00:42:09.040
and some violation of Senate
rules that they took him on.

00:42:09.040 --> 00:42:12.274
But a lot of people had
been ruined by then.

00:42:12.274 --> 00:42:13.690
AUDIENCE: Brief
follow up on that.

00:42:13.690 --> 00:42:15.370
Do you think it was
more-- so after he

00:42:15.370 --> 00:42:16.744
went after the
army, do you think

00:42:16.744 --> 00:42:19.660
it was the people
got tired of him,

00:42:19.660 --> 00:42:20.920
the politicians followed suit?

00:42:20.920 --> 00:42:22.600
Or do you think
it was politicians

00:42:22.600 --> 00:42:24.026
displaying some leadership?

00:42:27.269 --> 00:42:29.560
JAKE TAPPER: One of the
reasons the book is set in 1954

00:42:29.560 --> 00:42:31.934
is because he began that year
at the height of his power.

00:42:37.010 --> 00:42:39.520
There's a book by David Nichols
called "Ike Versus McCarthy"

00:42:39.520 --> 00:42:41.230
that I used as a basis
for some of the plot

00:42:41.230 --> 00:42:43.313
in the book, which is the
idea that Eisenhower was

00:42:43.313 --> 00:42:47.230
the whole time setting a plot,
setting a trap for McCarthy,

00:42:47.230 --> 00:42:51.270
and the Army-McCarthy
hearings were part of that.

00:42:51.270 --> 00:42:54.070
Ultimately, I think
McCarthy gave them

00:42:54.070 --> 00:42:58.690
an opening in the
Army-McCarthy hearings,

00:42:58.690 --> 00:43:00.760
and the US Senate took it.

00:43:00.760 --> 00:43:06.640
But like I said, that
they tolerated a lot.

00:43:06.640 --> 00:43:09.340
George Marshall is a
hero of World War II.

00:43:09.340 --> 00:43:11.380
He's a hero of the post-war.

00:43:11.380 --> 00:43:14.000
And Joe McCarthy smeared him.

00:43:14.000 --> 00:43:18.130
He wrote a book about
him, just attacking him.

00:43:18.130 --> 00:43:21.340
And there was a
time in 1952, when

00:43:21.340 --> 00:43:24.040
Eisenhower, who was so
sick of McCarthy doing this

00:43:24.040 --> 00:43:28.900
to his friend and
mentor George Marshall,

00:43:28.900 --> 00:43:31.150
that Eisenhower was going
to say something about it

00:43:31.150 --> 00:43:34.360
during a campaign
appearance in Wisconsin.

00:43:34.360 --> 00:43:36.960
And McCarthy was
going to be onstage.

00:43:36.960 --> 00:43:39.340
And at the last minute,
the governor of Wisconsin

00:43:39.340 --> 00:43:44.560
heard about it and convinced
Eisenhower to take it out

00:43:44.560 --> 00:43:45.250
of his speech.

00:43:45.250 --> 00:43:46.625
And it was something
he regretted

00:43:46.625 --> 00:43:48.310
for the rest of his life.

00:43:48.310 --> 00:43:50.810
Although we have to give him
credit for going to Wisconsin,

00:43:50.810 --> 00:43:51.310
I guess.

00:43:54.560 --> 00:43:57.580
Little Hillary Clinton
joke there, sorry.

00:43:57.580 --> 00:43:59.890
But in any case,
my only point is,

00:43:59.890 --> 00:44:01.990
people are willing
to put up with a lot

00:44:01.990 --> 00:44:03.550
until all of a
sudden they're not.

00:44:03.550 --> 00:44:07.850
I don't know where
this US Congress is.

00:44:07.850 --> 00:44:11.390
SPEAKER: So I had a question
about the echoes of gun

00:44:11.390 --> 00:44:17.060
violence that both pervade your
book and what's going on today.

00:44:17.060 --> 00:44:19.910
It really struck me
as reading the book,

00:44:19.910 --> 00:44:22.765
this violence goes back all
the way through our history.

00:44:22.765 --> 00:44:23.540
JAKE TAPPER: Yeah.

00:44:23.540 --> 00:44:26.000
SPEAKER: Just the anecdotes
about William Taulbee

00:44:26.000 --> 00:44:27.085
earlier in the book.

00:44:27.085 --> 00:44:28.460
JAKE TAPPER: That's
a congressman

00:44:28.460 --> 00:44:31.027
who killed a reporter.

00:44:31.027 --> 00:44:31.610
SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:44:31.610 --> 00:44:33.569
And you think about
that in the context.

00:44:33.569 --> 00:44:34.610
JAKE TAPPER: In Congress.

00:44:34.610 --> 00:44:35.000
SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:44:35.000 --> 00:44:37.375
JAKE TAPPER: And the bloodstains
are still on the stairs.

00:44:37.375 --> 00:44:38.080
That's true.

00:44:38.080 --> 00:44:40.540
Yeah, once again,
look to the endnotes.

00:44:40.540 --> 00:44:43.130
Sorry.

00:44:43.130 --> 00:44:45.590
SPEAKER: And now here we are
today, and a couple of months

00:44:45.590 --> 00:44:47.639
ago you moderated the
town hall at Parkland.

00:44:47.639 --> 00:44:50.180
And I know you said it was one
of the hardest things you ever

00:44:50.180 --> 00:44:50.680
did.

00:44:50.680 --> 00:44:52.950
And I just wonder,
what can we do,

00:44:52.950 --> 00:44:55.620
where do we go from here,
and your thoughts on that?

00:44:55.620 --> 00:44:56.120
[SIGHS]

00:44:56.120 --> 00:44:57.940
JAKE TAPPER: OK.

00:44:57.940 --> 00:45:01.820
It was challenging just because
the emotions in the room

00:45:01.820 --> 00:45:04.230
were just so raw.

00:45:04.230 --> 00:45:07.550
You know, their daughters, and
sons, and brothers, and friends

00:45:07.550 --> 00:45:09.440
had been murdered
one week before,

00:45:09.440 --> 00:45:11.300
and everybody was so raw.

00:45:11.300 --> 00:45:15.980
And it was an opportunity
to facilitate them to allow

00:45:15.980 --> 00:45:18.590
them to speak truth to power.

00:45:18.590 --> 00:45:21.230
But it was difficult
just emotionally.

00:45:21.230 --> 00:45:23.690
I mean, again, much more
so for them than for me,

00:45:23.690 --> 00:45:27.980
but it was just tough to do,
to be around all that pain

00:45:27.980 --> 00:45:29.810
and heartache.

00:45:29.810 --> 00:45:33.570
I don't know what the solution
is to gun violence in America.

00:45:36.590 --> 00:45:38.810
I recognize that it's
a complicated problem,

00:45:38.810 --> 00:45:40.490
and it's probably a
lot more complicated

00:45:40.490 --> 00:45:46.640
than policymakers on either
side, on the extremes,

00:45:46.640 --> 00:45:48.260
want to make it seem.

00:45:48.260 --> 00:45:53.420
There is no way that
the US Senate, even

00:45:53.420 --> 00:45:56.450
under Democratic control,
would be willing to ban

00:45:56.450 --> 00:45:58.770
so-called "assault weapons."

00:45:58.770 --> 00:45:59.357
They won't.

00:45:59.357 --> 00:46:01.190
If the Democrats want
to control the Senate,

00:46:01.190 --> 00:46:02.390
they need to have
Democrats in there

00:46:02.390 --> 00:46:04.140
from places like West
Virginia and Montana

00:46:04.140 --> 00:46:06.097
who won't vote for those things.

00:46:06.097 --> 00:46:08.180
That said, there are a lot
of commonsense measures

00:46:08.180 --> 00:46:11.030
that it would seem, you would
think, would be able to get

00:46:11.030 --> 00:46:14.720
support, ones that the president
has expressed support for.

00:46:14.720 --> 00:46:18.170
And yet, when the cameras
are off, not so much.

00:46:18.170 --> 00:46:19.830
I don't have a solution.

00:46:19.830 --> 00:46:23.240
And I wish I did.

00:46:23.240 --> 00:46:25.880
Obviously, the
biggest intersection,

00:46:25.880 --> 00:46:28.880
it seems to me, where
there should be action

00:46:28.880 --> 00:46:37.220
is in the nexus between people
with violent emotional problems

00:46:37.220 --> 00:46:39.170
and their ability to get guns.

00:46:39.170 --> 00:46:43.370
And it seems to me that
the temporary restraining

00:46:43.370 --> 00:46:45.920
order that allows family
members to say to a judge

00:46:45.920 --> 00:46:48.620
or to a police officer, we're
worried about this person,

00:46:48.620 --> 00:46:51.950
and we think that they have
guns, and we're concerned,

00:46:51.950 --> 00:46:54.620
and they petition the court,
that that should be something.

00:46:54.620 --> 00:46:56.120
California
experimented with that

00:46:56.120 --> 00:46:59.690
or passed something like
that after the San--

00:46:59.690 --> 00:47:01.331
Santa Barbara or San Bernardino?

00:47:01.331 --> 00:47:02.330
SPEAKER: San Bernardino.

00:47:02.330 --> 00:47:03.040
JAKE TAPPER: San Berna--

00:47:03.040 --> 00:47:04.706
no, I forgot it was--
no, Santa Barbara.

00:47:04.706 --> 00:47:08.540
Santa Barbara, that
little misogynist

00:47:08.540 --> 00:47:10.890
who drove around
hitting, killing people.

00:47:10.890 --> 00:47:15.459
It was after him, because his
family knew he had problems.

00:47:15.459 --> 00:47:17.000
And the police went
to check him out,

00:47:17.000 --> 00:47:18.430
but they didn't
go into his room.

00:47:18.430 --> 00:47:19.910
Anyway, there are
things that can

00:47:19.910 --> 00:47:21.560
be done in that
nexus between people

00:47:21.560 --> 00:47:25.160
with violent emotional
and mental problems

00:47:25.160 --> 00:47:27.860
and the ease with which
anybody can get a gun.

00:47:27.860 --> 00:47:31.250
And it seems like that is an
area where policymakers should

00:47:31.250 --> 00:47:33.230
focus as much
attention as they can,

00:47:33.230 --> 00:47:37.500
because it seems to be the
area where there's a lot to do.

00:47:37.500 --> 00:47:41.000
But the truth of the matter is,
most gun deaths in this country

00:47:41.000 --> 00:47:44.086
are suicides, not murders.

00:47:44.086 --> 00:47:46.440
And I'm not saying
that's not as serious,

00:47:46.440 --> 00:47:51.390
but when people say 30,000 a
year, 2/3 of them are suicides.

00:47:51.390 --> 00:47:55.910
And most of the gun deaths are
not mass weapon slaughters.

00:47:55.910 --> 00:47:59.390
They are handguns in
individual occurrences,

00:47:59.390 --> 00:48:04.910
oftentimes men killing
women in their lives.

00:48:04.910 --> 00:48:10.310
So Parkland, that kind of
thing doesn't happen as much,

00:48:10.310 --> 00:48:12.170
in terms of body count.

00:48:12.170 --> 00:48:15.560
The more serious thing has
to do with individual handgun

00:48:15.560 --> 00:48:16.700
shooting incidents.

00:48:16.700 --> 00:48:19.850
And I don't know
what can be done.

00:48:19.850 --> 00:48:21.290
SPEAKER: OK.

00:48:21.290 --> 00:48:22.340
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:48:22.340 --> 00:48:25.970
Big fan, since you were a
guest host on ABC "This Week."

00:48:25.970 --> 00:48:27.684
JAKE TAPPER: Thanks.

00:48:27.684 --> 00:48:29.100
AUDIENCE:
Non-Washington question.

00:48:29.100 --> 00:48:31.550
I mean, Washington is
polarized, but the country

00:48:31.550 --> 00:48:32.584
is pretty polarized too.

00:48:32.584 --> 00:48:34.250
It's probably about
eight states, right,

00:48:34.250 --> 00:48:36.860
where you have a chance
of moving the needle.

00:48:36.860 --> 00:48:39.830
My brother lives in Missouri,
and he canceled his cable bill

00:48:39.830 --> 00:48:41.840
because any time
any election comes,

00:48:41.840 --> 00:48:44.085
it's wall to wall political ads.

00:48:44.085 --> 00:48:45.710
JAKE TAPPER: Yeah.

00:48:45.710 --> 00:48:48.140
AUDIENCE: So this seems
like a much harder question.

00:48:48.140 --> 00:48:51.754
If I ask myself,
I'm fairly liberal,

00:48:51.754 --> 00:48:53.420
even if I was
conservative in the state,

00:48:53.420 --> 00:48:55.790
I have no shot of
doing anything.

00:48:55.790 --> 00:48:58.610
If everybody is
like me, then what

00:48:58.610 --> 00:49:03.200
is the principle that
causes states to shift?

00:49:03.200 --> 00:49:05.750
I mean, because if
you don't remove

00:49:05.750 --> 00:49:09.160
the polarization in
the people, you're

00:49:09.160 --> 00:49:12.350
never going to remove the
polarization in politics.

00:49:12.350 --> 00:49:13.520
JAKE TAPPER: Mm-hm.

00:49:13.520 --> 00:49:14.720
I don't know.

00:49:14.720 --> 00:49:17.060
I'm not an expert on
demographic shifts

00:49:17.060 --> 00:49:20.210
or why certain states
become more liberal or more

00:49:20.210 --> 00:49:21.500
conservative.

00:49:21.500 --> 00:49:26.840
I've seen it happen in my life
as the Northeast has become

00:49:26.840 --> 00:49:30.500
decidedly more progressive,
and other parts of the country

00:49:30.500 --> 00:49:34.830
have been decidedly
more conservative.

00:49:34.830 --> 00:49:39.080
I mean, I'm old enough to
remember Democrats, not just

00:49:39.080 --> 00:49:40.910
Democrats, white
Democrats representing

00:49:40.910 --> 00:49:42.530
parts of the South.

00:49:42.530 --> 00:49:45.170
Mainly, it seems like
the Southern Democrats,

00:49:45.170 --> 00:49:46.640
a lot of them are
African American

00:49:46.640 --> 00:49:48.681
because they represent
African American districts

00:49:48.681 --> 00:49:50.150
redistricted.

00:49:50.150 --> 00:49:56.360
And I'm old enough to remember
liberal Republicans, when

00:49:56.360 --> 00:49:59.990
Susan Collins was not an
endangered species, when

00:49:59.990 --> 00:50:01.900
there were a lot of--

00:50:01.900 --> 00:50:03.650
AUDIENCE: There are
none in the House now.

00:50:03.650 --> 00:50:04.860
And there were a lot.

00:50:04.860 --> 00:50:06.350
JAKE TAPPER: Yeah, not
from New England, right?

00:50:06.350 --> 00:50:07.950
I mean, you have
Charlie Baker here,

00:50:07.950 --> 00:50:10.260
so it's not like
it can't be done.

00:50:10.260 --> 00:50:13.490
It can be done.

00:50:13.490 --> 00:50:15.260
I don't know why it happens.

00:50:15.260 --> 00:50:18.050
I think it just has to do with
one of the things going on

00:50:18.050 --> 00:50:21.320
is just people siloing
themselves off from people

00:50:21.320 --> 00:50:23.270
with different points of view.

00:50:23.270 --> 00:50:26.330
Whether it's cable news,
or news in general,

00:50:26.330 --> 00:50:30.560
or websites, or
politicians, we just

00:50:30.560 --> 00:50:33.620
seem to be becoming a more
tribal society in terms

00:50:33.620 --> 00:50:36.720
of our political beliefs.

00:50:36.720 --> 00:50:39.880
Yeah, I mean,
every four years, I

00:50:39.880 --> 00:50:42.720
hear about how Missouri
is a purple state,

00:50:42.720 --> 00:50:45.440
and I never believe it.

00:50:45.440 --> 00:50:48.890
But I have lived long enough to
see purple states go from red

00:50:48.890 --> 00:50:50.520
to blue and from blue to red.

00:50:50.520 --> 00:50:52.250
I mean, I have lived
long enough to see.

00:50:52.250 --> 00:50:55.790
I remember when John Kerry was
trying to get Colorado in 2004.

00:50:55.790 --> 00:50:59.690
And I thought he was on
drugs, but now Colorado

00:50:59.690 --> 00:51:03.470
is pretty solidly
purple, if not blue.

00:51:06.823 --> 00:51:10.760
And amazingly, I can't
even believe it happened.

00:51:10.760 --> 00:51:12.260
Barack Obama won Indiana.

00:51:12.260 --> 00:51:14.210
I mean, it did happen in 2008.

00:51:14.210 --> 00:51:19.640
So different candidates
can win over a populace

00:51:19.640 --> 00:51:21.051
based on who they are.

00:51:21.051 --> 00:51:22.550
But generally
speaking, I just think

00:51:22.550 --> 00:51:24.983
we're becoming more tribal.

00:51:24.983 --> 00:51:26.950
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:51:26.950 --> 00:51:31.450
AUDIENCE: So I'm curious about,
as your career has spanned time

00:51:31.450 --> 00:51:33.960
before the internet
was a big thing,

00:51:33.960 --> 00:51:35.950
and then now we
have Twitter, and it

00:51:35.950 --> 00:51:40.020
feels like everything
has just accelerated.

00:51:40.020 --> 00:51:42.040
The news cycle is
faster and faster.

00:51:42.040 --> 00:51:49.030
And I'm curious both how
you feel about that and also

00:51:49.030 --> 00:51:52.219
how that factored in when you
go back and look at the '50s,

00:51:52.219 --> 00:51:54.010
researching that and
then writing about it,

00:51:54.010 --> 00:51:58.060
in a world when we didn't
have Twitter and things

00:51:58.060 --> 00:51:59.530
weren't happening so quickly.

00:51:59.530 --> 00:52:01.749
A great example of that
would be Scott Pruitt.

00:52:01.749 --> 00:52:03.790
There's so much news about
Scott Pruitt one week,

00:52:03.790 --> 00:52:06.880
and then by Friday, it was
gone, because everybody had

00:52:06.880 --> 00:52:08.261
moved on to the next scandal.

00:52:08.261 --> 00:52:10.510
JAKE TAPPER: Yeah, I mean,
the Scott Pruitt situation,

00:52:10.510 --> 00:52:12.051
I can just tell you
as somebody who's

00:52:12.051 --> 00:52:14.620
responsible for an hour
of news show every day,

00:52:14.620 --> 00:52:18.520
is that President Trump pushes
Scott Pruitt off our deck.

00:52:18.520 --> 00:52:19.916
I mean, President Trump--

00:52:19.916 --> 00:52:21.540
we'll have, like, a
Scott Pruitt piece.

00:52:21.540 --> 00:52:23.915
This has happened now at least
twice, if not three times,

00:52:23.915 --> 00:52:27.520
that we had a piece about
Scott Pruitt's five most

00:52:27.520 --> 00:52:29.744
recent scandals, and
then President Trump

00:52:29.744 --> 00:52:31.660
did or said something,
and we didn't have time

00:52:31.660 --> 00:52:32.620
to get to Scott Pruitt.

00:52:32.620 --> 00:52:35.119
I mean, so Donald Trump is the
best thing that ever happened

00:52:35.119 --> 00:52:36.796
to Scott Pruitt in every way.

00:52:36.796 --> 00:52:39.080
[LAUGHTER]

00:52:39.080 --> 00:52:42.520
You know, it's funny because my
first job in journalism was--

00:52:42.520 --> 00:52:46.540
after freelance-- was I worked
for "Washington City Paper."

00:52:46.540 --> 00:52:48.010
And then I worked for salon.com.

00:52:48.010 --> 00:52:52.030
It was very different
than what it is today.

00:52:52.030 --> 00:52:54.710
It was much more--

00:52:54.710 --> 00:52:55.910
it was not ideological.

00:52:55.910 --> 00:52:57.250
It was just a lot of
different points of view.

00:52:57.250 --> 00:52:59.030
It leaned left, because it
was based in San Francisco,

00:52:59.030 --> 00:53:00.905
but it was a lot of
different points of view.

00:53:00.905 --> 00:53:04.660
And I'll tell you, it was
amazing working for salon.com

00:53:04.660 --> 00:53:07.630
in 1999 and 2000, covering
the presidential race,

00:53:07.630 --> 00:53:09.940
because at the time--

00:53:09.940 --> 00:53:12.400
and some people here might be
too young to remember this--

00:53:12.400 --> 00:53:16.450
at the time, newspapers,
other websites,

00:53:16.450 --> 00:53:19.190
only updated once a day.

00:53:19.190 --> 00:53:20.800
So I would be on
the road with people

00:53:20.800 --> 00:53:23.470
from the "LA Times" and "The
New York Times" and "ABC News,"

00:53:23.470 --> 00:53:28.210
"Washington Post," whatever,
and something would happen,

00:53:28.210 --> 00:53:28.990
and I would write.

00:53:28.990 --> 00:53:31.870
I would write a piece on
my laptop and send it in,

00:53:31.870 --> 00:53:35.120
and it would post on
Salon within an hour.

00:53:35.120 --> 00:53:38.710
And I would scoop
everybody, not because I

00:53:38.710 --> 00:53:42.040
was such a great reporter, but
because their websites weren't

00:53:42.040 --> 00:53:45.100
going to update until the
next morning at 6:00 AM.

00:53:45.100 --> 00:53:46.480
It's crazy.

00:53:46.480 --> 00:53:48.760
And then I remember
"The Washington Post"

00:53:48.760 --> 00:53:52.690
took this amazing step
that every day at 4:00

00:53:52.690 --> 00:53:56.590
they were going
to do one update.

00:53:56.590 --> 00:54:02.800
So it was awesome for me,
being on the tip of the spear

00:54:02.800 --> 00:54:04.540
of the internet journalism.

00:54:04.540 --> 00:54:08.680
Because all these dinosaurs
that I was competing with

00:54:08.680 --> 00:54:11.590
didn't realize
what was going on.

00:54:11.590 --> 00:54:13.570
Ultimately, they did.

00:54:13.570 --> 00:54:16.690
Now the news cycle is crazy.

00:54:16.690 --> 00:54:20.770
But when writing the book, the
most you could hope for then

00:54:20.770 --> 00:54:22.664
was there was an
afternoon newspaper.

00:54:22.664 --> 00:54:24.580
There was "The Washington
Post" in the morning

00:54:24.580 --> 00:54:29.080
and "The Washington Star"
in the afternoon in DC.

00:54:29.080 --> 00:54:35.350
And I mean, the news,
early on, the evening news

00:54:35.350 --> 00:54:37.150
was 15 minutes.

00:54:37.150 --> 00:54:40.690
And then they adapted it
to become half an hour.

00:54:40.690 --> 00:54:47.200
So it was just like a glacier
moving, the news in that era,

00:54:47.200 --> 00:54:49.780
compared to what we
deal with today, where

00:54:49.780 --> 00:54:53.080
I'm getting the shakes because
I want to go to my phone

00:54:53.080 --> 00:54:55.180
right now and find
what has happened

00:54:55.180 --> 00:54:57.940
in the last hour and a half.

00:54:57.940 --> 00:55:00.850
What has President Trump done?

00:55:00.850 --> 00:55:02.200
What is going on in the world?

00:55:02.200 --> 00:55:03.350
Because it changes.

00:55:03.350 --> 00:55:05.770
We'll be in the
middle of a show.

00:55:05.770 --> 00:55:09.040
I remember one time just in
the last couple of months,

00:55:09.040 --> 00:55:10.690
at the top of the
show, I just laid out

00:55:10.690 --> 00:55:13.420
all the huge events
that had happened just

00:55:13.420 --> 00:55:16.750
in the last 24 hours.

00:55:16.750 --> 00:55:18.460
And that was in our A block.

00:55:18.460 --> 00:55:23.300
And by our C block,
Hope Hicks had resigned.

00:55:23.300 --> 00:55:25.300
And I said, "remember
when I did that commentary

00:55:25.300 --> 00:55:26.770
six months ago about all the--

00:55:26.770 --> 00:55:27.269
oh, wait.

00:55:27.269 --> 00:55:29.206
That was 15 minutes ago."

00:55:29.206 --> 00:55:31.330
I mean, that's what it
feels like, this news cycle.

00:55:31.330 --> 00:55:32.830
It's just a different era.

00:55:32.830 --> 00:55:35.260
By the way, this
has to be it, right?

00:55:35.260 --> 00:55:39.700
I mean, we can't get any
more insane than this?

00:55:39.700 --> 00:55:41.830
At a certain point,
it would have

00:55:41.830 --> 00:55:44.410
to actually be traveling back
in time or something like that.

00:55:44.410 --> 00:55:49.720
This is as crazy as it
gets, I would think.

00:55:49.720 --> 00:55:52.517
SPEAKER: I think we have time
for about one more question.

00:55:52.517 --> 00:55:53.350
AUDIENCE: All right.

00:55:53.350 --> 00:55:54.730
I hate to be the last
question with this,

00:55:54.730 --> 00:55:56.830
but I can I ask you
about Kellyanne Conway?

00:55:56.830 --> 00:55:59.350
JAKE TAPPER: Sure.

00:55:59.350 --> 00:56:01.930
AUDIENCE: So I think last
