I thought we were
making progress.

00:57:59.410 --> 00:57:59.730
Here we are.

00:57:59.730 --> 00:58:00.730
We're making progress.

00:58:00.730 --> 00:58:02.688
She's not disputing the
fact that the president

00:58:02.688 --> 00:58:04.480
tells lots of lies.

00:58:04.480 --> 00:58:07.500
And Roy Blunt, Senate
Republican leadership,

00:58:07.500 --> 00:58:09.580
was in the next interview.

00:58:09.580 --> 00:58:12.820
Also, "Does it bother you that
the president lies so much?"

00:58:12.820 --> 00:58:13.601
was my question.

00:58:13.601 --> 00:58:15.100
"It would bother
me a lot more if we

00:58:15.100 --> 00:58:16.350
weren't getting so much done."

00:58:16.350 --> 00:58:18.640
So I mean, we've made progress.

00:58:18.640 --> 00:58:19.740
[LAUGHTER]

00:58:19.740 --> 00:58:23.040
They're acknowledging that
the president tells lies.

00:58:23.040 --> 00:58:25.840
I felt like a small
victory there.

00:58:25.840 --> 00:58:31.070
Third, 63 million
people voted for Trump.

00:58:31.070 --> 00:58:34.780
I don't think it's not
worthwhile to have the Trump

00:58:34.780 --> 00:58:39.650
point of view represented
on any number of issues,

00:58:39.650 --> 00:58:40.319
including hers.

00:58:40.319 --> 00:58:42.610
She was trying to explain
what the president meant when

00:58:42.610 --> 00:58:45.160
he was on Air Force
One and he said, "No,

00:58:45.160 --> 00:58:47.470
he didn't know
about the payment."

00:58:47.470 --> 00:58:48.940
You know, whatever.

00:58:48.940 --> 00:58:51.700
And then fourth-- and this
one is actually, I think,

00:58:51.700 --> 00:58:53.780
the most important to me--

00:58:53.780 --> 00:58:57.520
I think there is value in a
news anchor challenging people

00:58:57.520 --> 00:59:00.260
in power, even if--

00:59:00.260 --> 00:59:05.744
this isn't an Aaron Sorkin
scripted Sunday talk show.

00:59:05.744 --> 00:59:07.660
I mean, she's not going
to say, "You're right.

00:59:07.660 --> 00:59:08.690
He's a liar.

00:59:08.690 --> 00:59:10.253
What am I doing?"

00:59:10.253 --> 00:59:13.704
[LAUGHTER]

00:59:15.950 --> 00:59:19.340
But I think viewers
can get something out

00:59:19.340 --> 00:59:22.640
of feeling
represented, at least.

00:59:22.640 --> 00:59:25.950
Why does he tell these lies?

00:59:25.950 --> 00:59:28.940
For instance, the
president said that Obama

00:59:28.940 --> 00:59:31.490
had tried to get these three
hostages out of North Korea

00:59:31.490 --> 00:59:34.430
and failed, but he
was going to do it.

00:59:34.430 --> 00:59:37.730
Two of them were taken
hostage during the Trump

00:59:37.730 --> 00:59:39.030
administration.

00:59:39.030 --> 00:59:43.940
So that would have been a neat
trick, if Obama had actually

00:59:43.940 --> 00:59:47.280
anticipated and not
been able to prevent it.

00:59:47.280 --> 00:59:52.350
So just to say it, just to
say, it's not true, it's a lie.

00:59:52.350 --> 00:59:54.320
I think there is value in that.

00:59:54.320 --> 00:59:57.230
That said, it's not as
though it isn't a discussion

00:59:57.230 --> 01:00:02.240
that we have every time
we book a Trump guest.

01:00:02.240 --> 01:00:04.349
It is a discussion that we have.

01:00:04.349 --> 01:00:05.390
What are we going to get?

01:00:05.390 --> 01:00:06.510
Why would we do it?

01:00:06.510 --> 01:00:09.350
We turn down people.

01:00:09.350 --> 01:00:11.844
But anyway, that's my reasoning.

01:00:11.844 --> 01:00:13.010
AUDIENCE: All right, thanks.

01:00:13.010 --> 01:00:15.124
JAKE TAPPER: Thank you.

01:00:15.124 --> 01:00:17.040
SPEAKER: Thanks so much,
everyone, for coming.

01:00:17.040 --> 01:00:17.750
JAKE TAPPER: Thanks for
being here, everyone.

01:00:17.750 --> 01:00:18.890
I really appreciate it.

01:00:18.890 --> 01:00:21.640
[APPLAUSE]

